{"title_page": "Lady Bird (film)", "text_new": "{{about|the 2017 film|the 1927 film|The Ladybird (film)}}\n{{short description|2017 film by Greta Gerwig}}\n{{Use American English|date=October 2017}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name = Lady Bird\n| image = Lady Bird poster.jpeg\n| alt = \n| caption = Theatrical release poster\n| director = [[Greta Gerwig]]\n| producer = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Scott Rudin]]\n* [[Eli Bush]]\n* [[Evelyn O'Neill]]\n}}\n| writer = Greta Gerwig\n| starring = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Saoirse Ronan]]\n* [[Laurie Metcalf]]\n* [[Tracy Letts]]\n* [[Lucas Hedges]]\n* [[Timoth\u00e9e Chalamet]]\n* [[Beanie Feldstein]]\n* [[Stephen Henderson (actor)|Stephen McKinley Henderson]]\n* [[Lois Smith]]\n}} <!--PER POSTER BILLING BLOCK-->\n| music = [[Jon Brion]]\n| cinematography = Sam Levy\n| editing = Nick Houy\n| studio = {{Plainlist|\n* [[IAC (company)|IAC Films]]\n* [[Scott Rudin Productions]]\n* Management 360\n}}\n| distributor = [[A24 (company)|A24]]\n| released = {{Film date|2017|09|01|[[Telluride Film Festival|Telluride]]|2017|11|3|United States}}\n| runtime = 94 minutes<!-- 94m 23s --><ref name=\"bbfc\">{{cite web|url=https://bbfc.co.uk/releases/lady-bird-2017|title=LADY BIRD - British Board of Film Classification|author=|date=|website=bbfc.co.uk|accessdate=May 28, 2019}}</ref>\n| country = United States\n| language = English\n| budget = $10&nbsp;million<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/features/lady-bird-how-greta-gerwig-created-2002-tell-her-coming-age-story-1055561|title='Lady Bird': How Greta Gerwig Re-created 2002 to Tell Her Coming-of-Age Story|quote=the budget (nearly $10 million in financing, thanks to Barry Diller's IAC)|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|first=Mia|last=Galuppo|date=November 10, 2017|accessdate=November 10, 2017}}</ref>\n| gross = $79 million<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=ladybird.htm |title=''Lady Bird'' (2017)|website=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=November 13, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Lady Bird''''' is a 2017 American [[Coming-of-age story|coming-of-age]] [[comedy-drama]] film written and directed by [[Greta Gerwig]] in her solo directorial debut. The film stars an [[ensemble cast]] that includes [[Saoirse Ronan]], [[Laurie Metcalf]], [[Tracy Letts]], [[Lucas Hedges]], [[Timoth\u00e9e Chalamet]], [[Beanie Feldstein]], [[Stephen McKinley Henderson]], and [[Lois Smith]]. Set in [[Sacramento, California]], between the fall of 2002 and the summer of 2003, it is a [[Coming-of-age story|coming-of-age]] story of a high school [[twelfth grade|senior]] and her strained relationship with her mother.\n\nThe film premiered at the [[Telluride Film Festival]] on September 1, 2017, and was released in the United States on November 3, 2017, by [[A24 (company)|A24]]. Critics praised Gerwig's screenplay and direction, and the performances of Ronan and Metcalf. ''Lady Bird'' was chosen by the [[National Board of Review]], the [[American Film Institute]], and [[Time (magazine)|''Time'']] magazine as one of the ten best films of the year.<ref name=\"AFI\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.afi.com/afiawards/AFI-Awards-2017.aspx|title=AFI Awards 2017|website=[[American Film Institute|AFI]]|accessdate=December 8, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171208174824/http://www.afi.com/afiawards/AFI-Awards-2017.aspx|archive-date=December 8, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalboardofreview.org/2017/11/national-board-review-announces-2017-award-winners/ |title=National Board of Review Announces 2017 Award Winners |publisher=[[National Board of Review]] |date=November 28, 2017 |accessdate=December 7, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Zacharek|first=Stephanie|authorlink=Stephanie Zacharek|url=http://time.com/5045566/top-10-movies-2017/|title=The Top 10 Movies of 2017|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|date=December 7, 2017|accessdate=December 13, 2017}}</ref> At the [[90th Academy Awards]], it earned five nominations: [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]], [[Academy Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]] (for Ronan), [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Supporting Actress]] (for Metcalf), [[Academy Award for Best Original Screenplay|Best Original Screenplay]], and [[Academy Award for Best Director|Best Director]]. At the [[75th Golden Globe Awards]], the film won two awards\u2014[[Golden Globe Award for Best Motion Picture&nbsp;\u2013 Musical or Comedy|Best Motion Picture (Musical or Comedy)]] and [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Motion Picture Musical or Comedy|Best Actress (Motion-Picture Musical or Comedy)]] (for Ronan)\u2014and was nominated for two others. It was also nominated for three [[British Academy Film Awards]].\n\n==Plot==\nIn 2002, Christine McPherson is a senior at a Catholic high school in [[Sacramento, California]]. She gives herself the name \"Lady Bird\" and longs to attend a prestigious college in \"a city with culture\" somewhere on the east coast, despite her family's financial struggles. Her mother Marion often tells her that she is ungrateful for what she has. Lady Bird and her best friend Julie join their school theater program, where Lady Bird develops a crush on classmate Danny O'Neill. This grows into a romantic relationship, and Lady Bird disappoints Marion by spending her last Thanksgiving before graduation with Danny's wealthy family instead of her own. After the opening night of \"[[Merrily We Roll Along (musical)|Merrily We Roll Along]],\" their relationship ends when Lady Bird and Julie discover her boyfriend kissing another boy in a bathroom stall.\n\nAt the behest of Marion, Lady Bird takes a job at a coffee shop; there, she meets Kyle, and they begin dating. Lady Bird abandons Julie and ditches tryouts for the new play to bond with Jenna Walton, a popular girl, and they vandalize a nun's car. As Lady Bird grows closer to Kyle and Jenna, she gradually deserts Julie, and she drops out of the theater program. She confronts Danny, but consoles him after he begins sobbing and expresses his struggle in [[coming out]], and they become friends again.\n\nAt a house party, while kissing, Kyle implies to Lady Bird that he has never had sex; he denies having said this when she later loses her virginity to him, which upsets her, and she cries in her mom's arms afterwards. When Lady Bird is suspended from school for speaking up at a pro-life assembly, Jenna tries to visit her at home, but discovers Lady Bird had claimed Danny's grandmother's house as hers. Lady Bird admits to the lie, and Jenna agrees to forgive her because of their mutual friendship with Kyle.\n\nLady Bird learns that her father Larry has lost his job and has been battling depression for years. She applies to East Coast colleges, despite Marion's insistence that the family cannot afford the fees, with the help of her father, who fills out her financial aid applications without Marion knowing. Lady Bird is accepted into [[UC Davis]], but is upset because she feels it is too close to home. Learning she is on the wait list for a New York college, she does not share the news with her mother, fearing her response. Lady Bird sets out for her prom with Kyle, Jenna, and Jenna's boyfriend Jonah, but the other three decide to go to a house party instead. Lady Bird originally agrees, then changes her mind and speaks up, saying she actually does want to go to prom. Lady Bird asks them to drop her off at Julie's apartment, where the two rekindle their friendship and go to the prom together.\n\nAfter graduation, Danny accidentally reveals Lady Bird's place on the wait list to Marion, who stops speaking to her daughter for the rest of the summer. On her eighteenth birthday, Lady Bird's father shares a cupcake with her, and she buys a pack of cigarettes, a [[Scratchcard|scratch-off ticket]], and an issue of ''[[Playgirl]]'' to celebrate reaching legal adulthood. Lady Bird learns she has been accepted into the New York college, and can afford tuition with financial aid with her father's help. Her parents take her to the airport, but Marion refuses to go inside to say goodbye. She has a change of heart and drives back, only to discover Lady Bird has already gone through security. She cries in her husband's arms, who consoles her that Lady Bird will come back.\n\nArriving in New York, Lady Bird finds several letters in her luggage; her mother had written and discarded them, but her father salvaged them. She begins using her birth name again, and is hospitalized after drinking heavily at a party. Leaving the hospital, she visits a [[Presbyterian]] church service and is moved to tears. She calls home and leaves an apologetic voicemail for her mother, thanking her for everything she has done for her.\n\n==Cast==\n{{div col}}\n* [[Saoirse Ronan]] as Christine \"Lady Bird\"{{efn|name=nickname|group=notes|The nickname does not derive from former [[First Lady of the United States|First Lady]] [[Lady Bird Johnson]], but the [[Mother Goose]] nursery rhyme [[Ladybird Ladybird]].<ref name=\"npr\">{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/transcript/transcript.php?storyId=564579012|title=Greta Gerwig Explores Mother-Daughter Love (And Angst) In 'Lady Bird'|accessdate=November 26, 2017|date=November 16, 2017|author=Terry Gross}}</ref>}} McPherson\n* [[Laurie Metcalf]] as Marion McPherson\n* [[Tracy Letts]] as Larry McPherson\n* [[Lucas Hedges]] as Danny O'Neill\n* [[Timoth\u00e9e Chalamet]] as Kyle Scheible\n* [[Beanie Feldstein]] as Julianne \"Julie\" Steffans\n* [[Lois Smith]] as Sister Sarah Joan\n* [[Stephen Henderson (actor)|Stephen McKinley Henderson]] as Father Leviatch\n* [[Odeya Rush]] as Jenna Walton\n* [[Jordan Rodrigues]] as Miguel McPherson\n* Marielle Scott as Shelly Yuhan\n* [[Andy Buckley]] as Uncle Matthew\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Production==\n\n===Development===\nGerwig spent years writing the screenplay. At one point it was over 350 pages long, and had the working title ''Mothers and Daughters''.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://www.indiewire.com/2017/10/greta-gerwig-lady-bird-inspired-by-youth-1201884532/|title=Greta Gerwig Explains How Much of Her Charming Coming-of-Age Film 'Lady Bird' Was Inspired by Her Own Youth|website=[[Indiewire.com]]|first=Kate|last=Erbland|date=October 6, 2017|accessdate=November 10, 2017}}</ref> In 2015, Gerwig and her team secured financing from [[IAC (company)|IAC Films]], who produced the film alongside [[Scott Rudin|Scott Rudin Productions]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/features/lady-bird-how-greta-gerwig-created-2002-tell-her-coming-age-story-1055561|title='Lady Bird': How Greta Gerwig Re-created 2002 to Tell Her Coming-of-Age Story|work=The Hollywood Reporter|access-date=January 12, 2018}}</ref> Gerwig's manager, [[Evelyn O'Neill]], also served as a producer.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nAlthough the film has been described as \"semi-autobiographical\",<ref name=\"RS\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/features/how-greta-gerwig-turned-the-personal-lady-bird-into-a-perfect-movie-w511093|title=How Greta Gerwig Turned the Personal 'Lady Bird' Into a Perfect Movie|website=[[Rolling Stone (magazine)|Rolling Stone]]|first=Esther|last=Zuckerman|date=November 5, 2017|accessdate=November 10, 2017}}</ref> Gerwig has said that \"nothing in the movie literally happened in my life, but it has a core of truth that resonates with what I know\".<ref name=\":0\" /> To prepare the cast and crew, Gerwig gave them her old high-school yearbooks, photos, and journals, as well as passages written by [[Joan Didion]], and took them on a tour of her hometown.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2017/11/greta-gerwig-lady-bird-design|title=How Greta Gerwig's Lady Bird Came to \"Look Like a Memory\"|website=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]|first=Julie|last=Miller|date=November 3, 2017|accessdate=November 10, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2017/11/greta-gerwig-lady-bird-joan-didion|title=How Joan Didion Shaped the World of Greta Gerwig's Lady Bird|last=Desta|first=Yohana|date=November 4, 2017|website=Vanity Fair|accessdate=November 10, 2017}}</ref> She told Sam Levy, [[Cinematographer|director of photography]] on the film, that she wanted it to feel \"like a memory,\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thefilmstage.com/features/lady-bird-cinematographer-sam-levy-on-greta-gerwig-frank-ocean-and-eric-rohmer/|title='Lady Bird' Cinematographer Sam Levy on Greta Gerwig, Frank Ocean, and \u00c9ric Rohmer|website=The Film Stage|first=Jordan|last=Raup|date=November 1, 2017|accessdate=November 10, 2017}}</ref> and said that she \"sought to offer a female counterpart to tales like ''[[The 400 Blows]]'' and ''[[Boyhood (film)|Boyhood]].''\"<ref name=\"RS\" /> The film was Gerwig's first as a solo director; in 2008, she had co-written and co-directed ''[[Nights and Weekends]]'' with [[Joe Swanberg]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Simran |last=Hans |title=Lady Bird review \u2013 a magical portrait of adolescence |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/feb/18/lady-bird-review-greta-gerwig-saoirse-ronan-laurie-metcalf-observer |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]] |date=February 18, 2018 |accessdate=February 21, 2018 |quote=\"''Lady Bird'' has been described as Greta Gerwig\u2019s directorial debut. Yet, with ... a co-director credit on Joe Swanberg's 2008 mumblecore drama ''Nights and Weekends'', it's not as though she is new to making movies.\"}}</ref>\n\n===Casting===\nIn September 2015, Gerwig met with [[Saoirse Ronan]] at the [[Toronto International Film Festival]], where they were promoting ''[[Maggie's Plan]]'' and [[Brooklyn (film)|''Brooklyn'']] respectively. They ran through the script in a hotel room, with Ronan reading the part of Lady Bird, and Gerwig reading the other characters. Gerwig realized by the second page that Ronan was the right choice for the lead.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-et-mn-greta-gerwig-lady-bird-telluride-20170903-htmlstory.html|title=Greta Gerwig talks about her directorial debut and casting Saoirse Ronan in 'Lady Bird'|website=[[Los Angeles Times]]|first=Josh|last=Rottenberg|date=September 3, 2017|accessdate=November 10, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://collider.com/greta-gerwig-interview-lady-bird/|title=Greta Gerwig on 'Lady Bird' and What Made Saoirse Ronan Perfect for the Title Role|last=Radish|first=Christina|date=November 8, 2017|website=[[Collider (website)|Collider]]|accessdate=November 10, 2017}}</ref> In January 2016, Ronan was cast.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/saoirse-ronan-greta-gerwig-lady-bird-1201686272/|title=Saoirse Ronan starring in Greta Gerwig's Drama Lady Bird|website=Variety|first=Dave|last=McNary|date=January 22, 2016|accessdate=September 28, 2017}}</ref> Gerwig met with [[Lucas Hedges]] and offered him his choice of the male parts. He chose Danny.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vulture.com/2017/11/lucas-hedges-on-lady-bird-three-billboards-and-boy-erased.html|title=Lucas Hedges Is Obsessed With His Lady Bird Co-stars, and Kept His Puka Shell Necklace|website=[[Vulture.com]]|first=Jackson|last=McHenry|date=November 8, 2017|accessdate=November 10, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wmagazine.com/story/lucas-hedges-lady-bird-greta-gerwig-madonna-oscars-party-gigi-hadid|title=Lucas Hedges Confesses He Was Almost Thrown Out of Madonna's Oscars Party|website=[[W Magazine]]|first=Lynn|last=Hirschberg|date=November 2, 2017|accessdate=November 10, 2017}}</ref> Gerwig cast [[Laurie Metcalf]] after seeing her theater work;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2017/11/lady-bird-laurie-metcalf-on-mom-role-and-roseanne-revival|title=Lady Bird's Laurie Metcalf on the Mom Role That Hit Close to Home and Roseanne's Revival|website=Vanity Fair|first=Nicole|last=Sperling|date=November 2, 2017|accessdate=November 10, 2017}}</ref> the rest of the cast\u2014including [[Tracy Letts]], [[Timoth\u00e9e Chalamet]], [[Beanie Feldstein]], [[John Karna]] and [[Jordan Rodrigues]]\u2014was announced in September 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2016/09/john-karna-lady-bird-natasha-liu-bordizzo-hotel-mumbai-1201814887/|title=John Karna Joins 'Lady Bird' Bevy; Natasha Liu Bordizzo Checks Into 'Hotel Mumbai'|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Amanda|last=N'Duka|date=September 7, 2016|accessdate=September 8, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2016/09/greta-gerwigs-lady-bird-jordan-rodrigues-pacific-rim-2-cailee-spaeny-1201820544/|title=Greta Gerwig's 'Lady Bird' Adds Jordan Rodrigues; Cailee Spaeny Cast In 'Pacific Rim: Maelstrom'|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Amanda|last=N'Duka|date=September 15, 2016|accessdate=September 15, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wmagazine.com/story/beanie-feldstein-jonah-hill-sister-lady-bird-movie-greta-gerwig|title=Lady Bird's Beanie Feldstein Has Boundless Potential (and the Enthusiasm to Match)|website=[[W Magazine]]|first=Lauren|last=McCarthy|date=November 2, 2017|accessdate=November 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\n[[Principal photography]] was scheduled to begin in March 2016, but was delayed to August due to Ronan's commitments to a performance of Arthur Miller's ''[[The Crucible]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ew.com/movies/2017/12/11/greta-gerwig-lady-bird-golden-globes-nomination/|title=Greta Gerwig wants to hug every Lady Bird crew member after Golden Globe nominations|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|first=Devan|last=Coggan|date=December 11, 2017|accessdate=December 11, 2017}}</ref> Filming began on August 30, 2016 in Sacramento, California for one week. Five weeks were spent on location in [[Los Angeles]],<ref name=\":1\" /> with additional shooting in [[New York City]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.backstage.com/resources/detail/productionlisting/lady-bird-85896/|title=Lady Bird|website=Backstage|accessdate=September 8, 2016}}</ref> Gerwig had wanted to shoot the movie on [[Super 16 film]], but due to budget constraints ultimately shot on the [[Arri Alexa]] Mini. In [[post-production]], the filmmakers emphasized digital [[Noise (electronics)|noise]] to create the effect of a copy of a photograph.<ref>{{Cite podcast|title=All the Way Home with Barry Jenkins & Greta Gerwig|url=https://a24films.com/notes/2018/02/episode-01-all-the-way-home-with-barry-jenkins-greta-gerwig|date=February 28, 2018|last=Gerwig|first=Greta|last2=Jenkins|first2=Barry|publisher=[[A24 (company)|a24]]|author-link2=Barry Jenkins}}</ref>\n\nRonan dyed her hair red for the role, and did not wear makeup to cover her [[acne]]; she has said she saw the film as \"a really good opportunity to let a teenager's face in a movie actually look like a teenager's face in real life\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2017/11/saoirse-ronan-lady-bird-in-character|title=Saoirse Ronan Reveals the Secrets Behind Her Stunning Lady Bird Transformation|website=Vanity Fair|first=Julie|last=Miller|date=November 9, 2017|accessdate=November 10, 2017}}</ref> Gerwig, using a technique she learned from the filmmaker [[Rebecca Miller]], arrived an hour before everyone else to put the actors and crew at ease by knowing exactly how the day would run. She also banned cell phones on the set, a policy borrowed from [[Noah Baumbach]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/greta-gerwig-on-lady-bird_us_59f9a6fee4b0b7f0915f6307|title=Greta Gerwig on \"Lady Bird\"|website=[[The Huffington Post]]|first=Neil|last=Minow|date=November 1, 2017|accessdate=November 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nIn July 2017, [[A24 (company)|A24]] acquired worldwide distribution rights to the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2017/07/lady-bird-greta-gerwig-saoirse-ronan-a24-1202130872/|title=A24 Lands Worldwide Rights To Greta Gerwig-Directed 'Lady Bird|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Mike|last=Fleming Jr|date=July 18, 2017|accessdate=July 18, 2017}}</ref> The film had its world premiere at the Telluride Film Festival on September 1, 2017,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2017/08/telluride-film-festival-2017-lineup-list-batle-of-the-sexes-1202158843/|title='Darkest Hour', 'Battle of the Sexes', 'Lady Bird' Among World Premieres in 2017 Lineup \u2013 Telluride Film Festival|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Pete|last=Hammond|date=August 31, 2017|accessdate=August 31, 2017}}</ref> and screened at the Toronto International Film Festival on September 8, 2017,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tiff.net/tiff/lady-bird/|title=Lady Bird|website=[[Toronto International Film Festival]]|accessdate=November 10, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612162703/https://www.tiff.net/tiff/lady-bird/|archive-date=June 12, 2018|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and at the [[New York Film Festival]] on October 8, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.filmlinc.org/nyff2017/films/lady-bird/|title=Lady Bird|website=[[New York Film Festival]]|accessdate=November 10, 2017}}</ref> [[Universal Pictures]] acquired international distribution rights to the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/festivals/focus-international-distribution-saoirse-ronan-lady-bird-1202554975/|title=Focus Takes International Rights on Saoirse Ronan's Lady Bird|website=Variety|accessdate= September 12, 2017}}</ref> It was released theatrically in the United States on November 3, 2017,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2017/09/lady-bird-greta-gerwig-release-date-november-1202175334/|title=Greta Gerwig's 'Lady Bird' Going a Week Earlier in November|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro|date=September 22, 2017|accessdate=September 22, 2017}}</ref> in the United Kingdom on February 16, 2018, and in Ireland on February 23, 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nme.com/news/film/critics-say-hyped-indie-film-lady-bird-2157499|title=What the critics have to say about hyped indie film 'Lady Bird'|last=Connick|first=Tom|date=November 8, 2017|work=NME|access-date=November 11, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\n''Lady Bird'' grossed $49 million in the United States and Canada, and $29.7 million in other territories, for a worldwide total of $78.6 million.<ref name=\"BOM\" />\n\nIn its limited opening weekend, it grossed $364,437 from four theaters, for a per-theater average of $91,109.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2017/11/greta-gerwig-lady-bird-gilbert-lbj-last-flag-flying-specialty-box-office-1202202222/|title=Greta Gerwig's 'Lady Bird' Takes Year's Best Per Theater Average Of $93K \u2013 Specialty Box Office|author=Brian Brooks|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|accessdate=November 5, 2017}}</ref> It had the second best theater average of 2017, and the highest ever for a film in limited release directed by a woman.<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2017/11/lady-bird-greta-gerwig-box-office-oscar-race-moonlight|title=How Greta Gerwig's Lady Bird Just Took a Big Leap Forward in the Oscar Race|author=Joanna Robinson|work=Vanity Fair|accessdate=November 6, 2017}}</ref> The film expanded to 37 theaters in its second weekend, and grossed a three-day total of $1.2&nbsp;million, finishing tenth at the box office.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://deadline.com/2017/11/thor-ragnarok-murder-on-the-orient-express-daddys-home-2-weekend-box-office-1202205662/|title='Daddy's Home 2' Higher Than 'The Orient Express' In A 'Ragnarok'-Ruled Weekend \u2013 Early Sunday AM Update|author=Anthony D'Alessandro|date=November 11, 2017|accessdate=November 11, 2017}}</ref> In its third weekend, the film expanded to 238 theaters, and grossed a three-day total of $2.5 million, finishing eighth at the box office.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2017/11/justice-league-coco-gal-gadot-wonder-roman-j-israel-esq-thanksgiving-box-office-1202212680/|title=Can \u2018Coco\u2019 Whip \u2018Justice League\u2019 For Top Spot Over Thanksgiving Stretch? \u2013 Box Office Preview|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=November 20, 2017|accessdate=November 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe film had its official wide release on November 24, playing in 724 theaters and making $4 million over the weekend ($5.4 million over the five-day [[Thanksgiving (United States)|Thanksgiving]] frame), finishing eleventh.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2017/11/coco-justice-league-wonder-thanksgiving-box-office-1202213755/|title=Thanksgiving B.O. At $268M, +3% Over 2016 Spurred By \u2018Coco\u2019 & Holdovers|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=November 26, 2017|accessdate=November 26, 2017}}</ref> Expanding to 1,194 theaters the following week the film grossed $4.3 million, returning to eighth place.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2017/12/coco-three-billboards-shape-of-water-wonder-post-thanksgiving-weekend-box-office-1202217467/|title=\u2018Coco\u2019 Looking At Sweet $26M+ As Specialty Sector Pops With Awards Contenders \u2013 Sunday Final|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=December 3, 2017|accessdate=December 3, 2017}}</ref> ''Lady Bird'' also became A24's highest-grossing film domestically, ahead of ''[[Moonlight (2016 film)|Moonlight]]'', which made $27.9 million.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.indiewire.com/2017/12/lady-bird-box-office-a24-moonlight-1201910789/|title=\u2018Lady Bird\u2019 Is Now A24\u2019s Highest-Grossing Film, Surpassing \u2018Moonlight\u2019|last=Nordine|first=Michael|date=December 24, 2017|work=IndieWire|access-date=December 29, 2017}}</ref> The weekend of January 27, 2018, following the announcement of the film's five Oscar nominations, it made $1.9 million (an increase over the previous week's $1.1 million).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2018/01/maze-runner-death-cure-weekend-box-office-1202269925/|title=Fox Controls Close To 40% Of Weekend B.O. Led By \u2018Maze Runner\u2019 & Oscar Holdovers; \u2018Hostiles\u2019 Gallops Past $10M|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=January 28, 2018|accessdate=January 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\n{{multiple image|caption_align=center|header_align=center\n|align = right\n|total_width = 300\n|image1 = Saoirse Ronan in 2018 (cropped).png\n|width1 = 380\n|height1 = 500\n|image2 = LaurieMetcalfFeb08 cropped.jpg\n|width2 = 431\n|height2 = 500\n|footer = [[Saoirse Ronan]] and [[Laurie Metcalf]]'s performances garnered widespread critical acclaim and earned them [[Academy Award]] nominations for [[Academy Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]] and [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Supporting Actress]], respectively.\n}}\n''Lady Bird'' received a standing ovation at its international premiere at the Toronto International Film Festival,<ref>{{cite web|title=Lady Bird Director Greta Gerwig knew right away that Saoirse Ronan was right for the job|url=http://www.thewrap.com/lady-bird-greta-gerwig-saoirse-ronan-right-for-the-job-exclusive-video/|work=TheWrap|accessdate=September 11, 2017}}</ref> and was praised for Ronan and Metcalf's performances, and Gerwig's direction.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/lady-bird-review-1035669|title='Lady Bird': Film Review {{!}} Telluride 2017|work=The Hollywood Reporter|access-date=September 8, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"VarietyTelluride\">{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/reviews/lady-bird-review-greta-gerwig-1202546609/|title=Telluride Film Review: Saoirse Ronan in \u2018Lady Bird\u2019|last=Debruge|first=Peter|date=September 4, 2017|work=Variety|access-date=September 8, 2017}}</ref> On [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film currently has an approval rating of 99% based on 384 reviews, with an average rating of 8.74/10. The website's critical consensus reads \"''Lady Bird'' delivers fresh insights about the turmoil of adolescence and reveals debuting writer-director Greta Gerwig as a fully formed filmmaking talent.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/lady_bird |title=Lady Bird (2017) |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]] |access-date=March 31, 2020}}</ref> On November 27, 2017, it became the most-reviewed film ever to remain at 100% on the site with 164 positive reviews, beating previous record holder ''[[Toy Story 2]]'', which had 163 positive reviews at the time.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://ew.com/movies/2017/11/27/lady-bird-rotten-tomatoes-record/|title='Lady Bird' sets Rotten Tomatoes record as best-reviewed movie of all time|last=Weldon|first=Sarah|date=November 27, 2017|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|accessdate=September 19, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> It [[List of films with a 100% rating on Rotten Tomatoes|stayed at 100%]] until the 196th review was negative.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2017/12/lady-bird-rotten-tomatoes-record-broken-bad-review-cole-smithey-1201906394/|title=\u2018Lady Bird\u2019 No Longer Has a Perfect 100% on Rotten Tomatoes (and Nobody is Happy About It)|last=Sharf|first=Zack|date=December 11, 2017|website=[[IndieWire]]|url-status=live|access-date=September 19, 2019}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a weighted average score of 94 out of 100, based on reviews from 50 critics, indicating \"universal acclaim.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/lady-bird|title=Lady Bird Reviews|work=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|url-status=live|accessdate=September 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[A.O. Scott]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' described ''Lady Bird'' as \"big-screen perfection&nbsp;... exceptionally well-written, full of wordplay and lively argument. Every line sounds like something a person might actually say, which means that the movie is also exceptionally well acted.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Review: Greta Gerwig\u2019s \u2018Lady Bird\u2019 Is Big-Screen Perfection|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/10/31/movies/lady-bird-review-greta-gerwig-saoirse-ronan.html|work= [[The New York Times]]|date=October 31, 2017|accessdate=November 21, 2017}}</ref> [[Todd McCarthy]] of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' wrote the film was \"modestly scaled but creatively ambitious\" and \"succeeds on its own terms as a piquant audience pleaser\", and gave praise to Ronan, whom he said \"just seems to keep getting better all the time.\"<ref>{{cite news|title='Lady Bird:' Film Review Telluride 2017|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/lady-bird-review-1035669/|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=October 30, 2017}}</ref> Peter Debruge of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' praised Gerwig's direction and script as well as Ronan's performance.<ref name=VarietyTelluride/> [[Mick LaSalle]] of the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'' wrote the film was \"simply beautiful\" and \"warm and inspired\", hailing the performances of Ronan and Metcalf as well as Gerwig's direction and screenplay.<ref>{{cite news|last=LaSalle|first=Mick|title=Gerwig's 'Lady Bird' is warm and inspired|url=http://www.sfchronicle.com/movies/article/Gerwig-s-Lady-Bird-is-warm-and-inspired-12343275.php|accessdate=December 8, 2017|newspaper=[[San Francisco Chronicle]]|date=November 8, 2017}}</ref>\n\n''[[The Washington Post]]''{{'}}s [[Ann Hornaday]] described the film as a \"triumph of style, sensibility and spirit\" while similarly praising Ronan's performance and Gerwig's direction.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/goingoutguide/movies/greta-gerwig-makes-a-triumphant-debut-as-a-director-with-coming-of-age-comedy-lady-bird/2017/11/07/8b8bf78a-bc0c-11e7-a908-a3470754bbb9_story.html|date=November 8, 2017|title=Greta Gerwig makes a triumphant debut as a solo director with \u2018Lady Bird\u2019|work=[[The Washington Post]]|publisher=Ann Hornaday|accessdate=}}</ref> [[Peter Travers]] of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' rated the film 3.5 out of four stars in which he deemed it as \"simply irresistible\" and complimented the film's plot and narrative while highlighting the performances of Ronan and Metcalf in which he stated as an \"[[Academy Awards|Oscar]] calling\" and Gerwig's direction as \"full-blown triumph\". He also declared it as one of the year's best films.<ref>{{cite web|first=Peter|last=Travers|authorlink=Peter Travers|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/reviews/peter-travers-lady-bird-is-the-coming-of-age-movie-of-2017-w510189|title='Lady Bird' Review: Greta Gerwig's Coming-of-Age Story Is Simply Irresistible|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=October 31, 2017}}</ref> [[Richard Roeper]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' called the film \"unique and original and fresh and wonderful\" and \"appealing\" while lauding the performances (particularly Metcalf and Letts) in which he remarked that \"There\u2019s no level of acting on a higher plane than what [Metcalf] and [Letts] achieve in this film. This is what greatness looks like.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://chicago.suntimes.com/entertainment/greta-gerwigs-lady-bird-so-appealing-we-cant-wait-to-see-her-next/|title=Greta Gerwig\u2019s \u2018Lady Bird\u2019 so appealing, we can\u2019t wait to see her next|author=[[Richard Roeper]]|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|date=November 9, 2017|accessdate=November 9, 2017}}</ref> [[Alonso Duralde]] of ''[[TheWrap]]'' remarked that \"Gerwig the actress skillfully pivots between the wacky and the poignant, so it's no surprise that Gerwig the auteur so delicately balances hilarity and heartbreak\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/lady-bird-review-greta-gerwig-saoirse-ronan-laurie-metcalf/|title=\u2018Lady Bird\u2019 Film Review: Greta Gerwig Crafts a Lovely Portrait of the Artist as a Young Woman|work=[[TheWrap]]|first=Alonso|last=Duralde|date=November 3, 2017|accessdate=December 8, 2017}}</ref>\n\nA [[BBC]] study described the film as the \"most overrated by critics\" among the 2018 Oscar nominees. This was based on the difference in aggregated scores given to it by critics and collated by Metacritic compared to the scores given to it by the public on the website [[IMDb]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-43146027|title= Oscars 2018: Lady Bird is 'most overrated' nominated film by critics|author= Clara Guibourg|date= March 3, 2018 |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=August 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{{Main|List of accolades received by Lady Bird (film)}}\n''Lady Bird'' garnered a variety of awards and nominations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/feature/2017-film-awards-and-nominations-scorecard?|title=Best of 2017: Film Awards and Nominations Scorecard|website=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=January 3, 2018}}</ref> The film was chosen by the [[National Board of Review]], the [[American Film Institute]], and ''Time'' magazine as one of the top 10 films of 2017.<ref name=\"AFI\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalboardofreview.org/2017/11/national-board-review-announces-2017-award-winners/|title=National Board of Review Announces 2017 Award Winners|date=November 28, 2017|publisher=[[National Board of Review]]|accessdate=December 7, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://time.com/5045566/top-10-movies-2017/|title=The Top 10 Movies of 2017|last=Zacharek|first=Stephanie|authorlink=Stephanie Zacharek|date=December 7, 2017|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|accessdate=December 13, 2017}}</ref> In 2018, ''Lady Bird'' was awarded [[The ReFrame Stamp]] in the [[The ReFrame Stamp#2017 Narrative & Animated Feature Recipients|2017 Narrative & Animated Feature]] category.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://womenandhollywood.com/reframe-spotlights-gender-balanced-films-and-tv-with-new-stamp/|title=ReFrame Spotlights Gender-Balanced Films and TV with New Stamp|last=|first=|date=June 8, 2018|website=womenandhollywood.com|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[90th Academy Awards]], it was nominated for [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]], [[Academy Award for Best Director|Best Director]] and [[Academy Award for Best Original Screenplay|Best Original Screenplay]] for Gerwig, [[Academy Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]] for Ronan, and [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Actress in a Supporting Role]] for Metcalf;<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/01/23/entertainment/greta-gerwig-lady-bird-oscar-nomination/index.html|title=Greta Gerwig's best director nomination is a huge deal|first=Sandra |last=Gonzalez|work=CNN|access-date=March 2, 2018}}</ref> Gerwig became the fifth woman nominated in the Best Director category.<ref name=\":2\" /> It did not win in any of the five categories in which it was nominated.\n\nThe film also received eight nominations at the [[23rd Critics' Choice Awards]], including [[Critics' Choice Movie Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]], [[Critics' Choice Movie Award for Best Director|Best Director]], [[Critics' Choice Movie Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]], [[Critics' Choice Movie Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Supporting Actress]], [[Critics' Choice Movie Award for Best Screenplay|Best Original Screenplay]], and [[Critics' Choice Movie Award for Best Acting Ensemble|Best Acting Ensemble]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://deadline.com/2017/12/critics-choice-awards-nominations-the-shape-of-water-dunkirk-this-is-us-netflix-1202220528/|title=Critics\u2019 Choice Awards Nominations: \u2018The Shape Of Water\u2019 Leads With 14; Netflix Tops TV Contenders|last=Hammond|first=Pete|date=December 6, 2017|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|accessdate=December 7, 2017}}</ref> At the [[75th Golden Globe Awards]], it was nominated for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Motion Picture \u2013 Musical or Comedy|Best Motion Picture \u2013 Musical or Comedy]] (won), [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Motion Picture Comedy or Musical|Best Actress \u2013 Musical or Comedy]] for Ronan (won), [[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actress \u2013 Motion Picture|Best Supporting Actress]] for Metcalf, and [[Golden Globe Award for Best Screenplay|Best Screenplay]].<ref name=\"GG\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/golden-globe-nominations-2018-nominees-full-list-1202634435/|title=Golden Globe Nominations: Complete List|last=Rubin|first=Rebecca|date=December 11, 2017|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=December 11, 2017}}</ref> At the [[24th Screen Actors Guild Awards]], it was nominated for [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Female Actor in a Leading Role|Outstanding Performance by a Female Actor in a Leading Role]] for Ronan, [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Female Actor in a Supporting Role|Outstanding Performance by a Female Actor in a Supporting Role]] for Metcalf, and [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Cast in a Motion Picture|Outstanding Performance by a Cast in a Motion Picture]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/sag-award-nominations-2018-full-list-1063931|title=SAG Award Nominations: The Complete List|date=December 13, 2017|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=December 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Potential sequels==\nIn February 2018, on an episode of ''The A24 Podcast'', Gerwig expressed interest in making [[spiritual successor]]s to ''Lady Bird'', saying \"I would like to do a quartet of Sacramento films\" modeled on the [[Neapolitan Novels]] of [[Elena Ferrante]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2018/02/greta-gerwig-elena-ferrante-lady-bird-sacramento-movies|title=Greta Gerwig Is Planning a Series of Spiritual Sequels to Lady Bird|last=Desta|first=Yohana|work=HWD|access-date=2018-03-30|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist|group=notes}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{sisterlinks|d=Q27480769|display=''Lady Bird''|c=Category:Lady Bird (film)|n=no|v=no|voy=no|m=no|mw=no|s=no|wikt=no|species=no|no}}\n* {{official}}\n* {{IMDb title}}\n* {{AllMovie title}}\n\n{{Greta Gerwig}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title = [[List of accolades received by Lady Bird (film)|Awards for ''Lady Bird'']]\n|list =\n{{Golden Globe Award Best Motion Picture Musical or Comedy}}\n{{National Society of Film Critics Award for Best Film}}\n{{New York Film Critics Circle Award for Best Film}}\n{{Vancouver Film Critics Circle Award for Best Film}}\n}}\n\n[[Category:2017 films]]\n[[Category:2010s comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:2010s coming-of-age comedy films]]\n[[Category:2010s coming-of-age drama films]]\n[[Category:2010s feminist films]]\n[[Category:2010s high school films]]\n[[Category:2010s independent films]]\n[[Category:2010s LGBT-related films]]\n[[Category:2010s teen comedy films]]\n[[Category:2010s teen drama films]]\n[[Category:A24 films]]\n[[Category:American comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:American coming-of-age films]]\n[[Category:American feminist films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American high school films]]\n[[Category:American teen comedy films]]\n[[Category:American teen drama films]]\n[[Category:American teen LGBT-related films]]<!--http://www.newnownext.com/lady-bird-gay-coming-out-scene/11/2017/-->\n[[Category:Best Musical or Comedy Picture Golden Globe winners]]\n[[Category:Films about parenting]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Greta Gerwig]]\n[[Category:Films featuring a Best Musical or Comedy Actress Golden Globe winning performance]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Scott Rudin]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Jon Brion]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2002]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2003]]\n[[Category:Films set in California]]\n[[Category:Films set in New York City]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Films shot in New York City]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Sacramento, California]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Greta Gerwig]]\n[[Category:Focus Features films]]\n[[Category:LGBT-related comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:LGBT-related coming-of-age films]]\n[[Category:2017 directorial debut films]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the 2017 film|the 1927 film|The Ladybird (film)}}\n{{short description|2017 film by Greta Gerwig}}\n{{Use American English|date=October 2017}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name = Lady Bird\n| image = Lady Bird poster.jpeg\n| alt = \n| caption = Theatrical release poster\n| director = [[Greta Gerwig]]\n| producer = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Scott Rudin]]\n* [[Eli Bush]]\n* [[Evelyn O'Neill]]\n}}\n| writer = Greta Gerwig\n| starring = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Saoirse Ronan]]\n* [[Laurie Metcalf]]\n* [[Tracy Letts]]\n* [[Lucas Hedges]]\n* [[Timoth\u00e9e Chalamet]]\n* [[Beanie Feldstein]]\n* [[Stephen Henderson (actor)|Stephen McKinley Henderson]]\n* [[Lois Smith]]\n}} <!--PER POSTER BILLING BLOCK-->\n| music = [[Jon Brion]]\n| cinematography = Sam Levy\n| editing = Nick Houy\n| studio = {{Plainlist|\n* [[IAC (company)|IAC Films]]\n* [[Scott Rudin Productions]]\n* Management 360\n}}\n| distributor = [[A24 (company)|A24]]\n| released = {{Film date|2017|09|01|[[Telluride Film Festival|Telluride]]|2017|11|3|United States}}\n| runtime = 94 minutes<!-- 94m 23s --><ref name=\"bbfc\">{{cite web|url=https://bbfc.co.uk/releases/lady-bird-2017|title=LADY BIRD - British Board of Film Classification|author=|date=|website=bbfc.co.uk|accessdate=May 28, 2019}}</ref>\n| country = United States\n| language = English\n| budget = $10&nbsp;million<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/features/lady-bird-how-greta-gerwig-created-2002-tell-her-coming-age-story-1055561|title='Lady Bird': How Greta Gerwig Re-created 2002 to Tell Her Coming-of-Age Story|quote=the budget (nearly $10 million in financing, thanks to Barry Diller's IAC)|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|first=Mia|last=Galuppo|date=November 10, 2017|accessdate=November 10, 2017}}</ref>\n| gross = $79 million<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=ladybird.htm |title=''Lady Bird'' (2017)|website=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=November 13, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Lady Bird''''' is a 2017 American [[Coming-of-age story|coming-of-age]] [[comedy-drama]] film written and directed by [[Greta Gerwig]] in her solo directorial debut. The film stars an [[ensemble cast]] that includes [[Saoirse Ronan]], [[Laurie Metcalf]], [[Tracy Letts]], [[Lucas Hedges]], [[Timoth\u00e9e Chalamet]], [[Beanie Feldstein]], [[Stephen McKinley Henderson]], and [[Lois Smith]]. Set in [[Sacramento, California]], between the fall of 2002 and the summer of 2003, it is a [[Coming-of-age story|coming-of-age]] story of a high school [[twelfth grade|senior]] and her strained relationship with her mother.\n\nThe film premiered at the [[Telluride Film Festival]] on September 1, 2017, and was released in the United States on November 3, 2017, by [[A24 (company)|A24]]. Critics praised Gerwig's screenplay and direction, and the performances of Ronan and Metcalf. ''Lady Bird'' was chosen by the [[National Board of Review]], the [[American Film Institute]], and [[Time (magazine)|''Time'']] magazine as one of the ten best films of the year.<ref name=\"AFI\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.afi.com/afiawards/AFI-Awards-2017.aspx|title=AFI Awards 2017|website=[[American Film Institute|AFI]]|accessdate=December 8, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171208174824/http://www.afi.com/afiawards/AFI-Awards-2017.aspx|archive-date=December 8, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalboardofreview.org/2017/11/national-board-review-announces-2017-award-winners/ |title=National Board of Review Announces 2017 Award Winners |publisher=[[National Board of Review]] |date=November 28, 2017 |accessdate=December 7, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Zacharek|first=Stephanie|authorlink=Stephanie Zacharek|url=http://time.com/5045566/top-10-movies-2017/|title=The Top 10 Movies of 2017|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|date=December 7, 2017|accessdate=December 13, 2017}}</ref> At the [[90th Academy Awards]], it earned five nominations: [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]], [[Academy Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]] (for Ronan), [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Supporting Actress]] (for Metcalf), [[Academy Award for Best Original Screenplay|Best Original Screenplay]], and [[Academy Award for Best Director|Best Director]]. At the [[75th Golden Globe Awards]], the film won two awards\u2014[[Golden Globe Award for Best Motion Picture&nbsp;\u2013 Musical or Comedy|Best Motion Picture (Musical or Comedy)]] and [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Motion Picture Musical or Comedy|Best Actress (Motion-Picture Musical or Comedy)]] (for Ronan)\u2014and was nominated for two others. It was also nominated for three [[British Academy Film Awards]].\n\n==Plot==\nIn 2002, Christine McPherson is a senior at a Catholic high school in [[Sacramento, California]]. She gives herself the name \"Lady Bird\" and longs to attend a prestigious college in \"a city with culture\" somewhere on the east coast, despite her family's financial struggles. Her mother Marion often tells her that she is ungrateful for what she has. Lady Bird and her best friend Julie join their school theater program, where Lady Bird develops a crush on classmate Danny O'Neill. This grows into a romantic relationship, and Lady Bird disappoints Marion by spending her last Thanksgiving before graduation with Danny's wealthy family instead of her own. After the opening night of \"[[Merrily We Roll Along (musical)|Merrily We Roll Along]],\" their relationship ends when Lady Bird and Julie discover her boyfriend kissing another boy in a bathroom stall.\n\nAt the behest of Marion, Lady Bird takes a job at a coffee shop; there, she meets Kyle, and they begin dating. Lady Bird abandons Julie and ditches tryouts for the new play to bond with Jenna Walton, a popular girl, and they vandalize a nun's car. As Lady Bird grows closer to Kyle and Jenna, she gradually deserts Julie, and she drops out of the theater program. She confronts Danny, but consoles him after he begins sobbing and expresses his struggle in [[coming out]], and they become friends again.\n\nAt a house party, while kissing, Kyle implies to Lady Bird that he has never had sex; he denies having said this when she later loses her virginity to him, which upsets her, and she cries in her mom's arms afterwards. When Lady Bird is suspended from school for speaking up at a pro-life assembly, Jenna tries to visit her at home, but discovers Lady Bird had claimed Danny's grandmother's house as hers. Lady Bird admits to the lie, and Jenna agrees to forgive her because of their mutual friendship with Kyle.\n\nLady Bird learns that her father Larry has lost his job and has been battling depression for years. She applies to East Coast colleges, despite Marion's insistence that the family cannot afford the fees, with the help of her father, who fills out her financial aid applications without Marion knowing. Lady Bird is accepted into [[UC Davis]], but is upset because she feels it is too close to home. Learning she is on the wait list for a New York college, she does not share the news with her mother, fearing her response. Lady Bird sets out for her prom with Kyle, Jenna, and Jenna\u2019s boyfriend Jonah, but the other three decide to go to a house party instead. Lady Bird originally agrees, then changes her mind and speaks up, saying she actually does want to go to prom. Lady Bird asks them to drop her off at Julie's apartment, where the two rekindle their friendship and go to the prom together.\n\nAfter graduation, Danny accidentally reveals Lady Bird\u2019s place on the wait list to Marion, who stops speaking to her daughter for the rest of the summer. On her eighteenth birthday, Lady Bird's father shares a cupcake with her, and she buys a pack of cigarettes, a [[Scratchcard|scratch-off ticket]], and an issue of ''[[Playgirl]]'' to celebrate reaching legal adulthood. Lady Bird learns she has been accepted into the New York college, and can afford tuition with financial aid with her father's help. Her parents take her to the airport, but Marion refuses to go inside to say goodbye. She has a change of heart and drives back, only to discover Lady Bird has already gone through security. She cries in her husband's arms, who consoles her that Lady Bird will come back.\n\nArriving in New York, Lady Bird finds several letters in her luggage; her mother had written and discarded them, but her father salvaged them. She begins using her birth name again, and is hospitalized after drinking heavily at a party. Leaving the hospital, she visits a [[Presbyterian]] church service and is moved to tears. She calls home and leaves an apologetic voicemail for her mother, thanking her for everything she has done for her.\n\n==Cast==\n{{div col}}\n* [[Saoirse Ronan]] as Christine \"Lady Bird\"{{efn|name=nickname|group=notes|The nickname does not derive from former [[First Lady of the United States|First Lady]] [[Lady Bird Johnson]], but the [[Mother Goose]] nursery rhyme [[Ladybird Ladybird]].<ref name=\"npr\">{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/transcript/transcript.php?storyId=564579012|title=Greta Gerwig Explores Mother-Daughter Love (And Angst) In 'Lady Bird'|accessdate=November 26, 2017|date=November 16, 2017|author=Terry Gross}}</ref>}} McPherson\n* [[Laurie Metcalf]] as Marion McPherson\n* [[Tracy Letts]] as Larry McPherson\n* [[Lucas Hedges]] as Danny O'Neill\n* [[Timoth\u00e9e Chalamet]] as Kyle Scheible\n* [[Beanie Feldstein]] as Julianne \"Julie\" Steffans\n* [[Lois Smith]] as Sister Sarah Joan\n* [[Stephen Henderson (actor)|Stephen McKinley Henderson]] as Father Leviatch\n* [[Odeya Rush]] as Jenna Walton\n* [[Jordan Rodrigues]] as Miguel McPherson\n* Marielle Scott as Shelly Yuhan\n* [[Andy Buckley]] as Uncle Matthew\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Production==\n\n===Development===\nGerwig spent years writing the screenplay. At one point it was over 350 pages long, and had the working title ''Mothers and Daughters''.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://www.indiewire.com/2017/10/greta-gerwig-lady-bird-inspired-by-youth-1201884532/|title=Greta Gerwig Explains How Much of Her Charming Coming-of-Age Film 'Lady Bird' Was Inspired by Her Own Youth|website=[[Indiewire.com]]|first=Kate|last=Erbland|date=October 6, 2017|accessdate=November 10, 2017}}</ref> In 2015, Gerwig and her team secured financing from [[IAC (company)|IAC Films]], who produced the film alongside [[Scott Rudin|Scott Rudin Productions]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/features/lady-bird-how-greta-gerwig-created-2002-tell-her-coming-age-story-1055561|title='Lady Bird': How Greta Gerwig Re-created 2002 to Tell Her Coming-of-Age Story|work=The Hollywood Reporter|access-date=January 12, 2018}}</ref> Gerwig's manager, [[Evelyn O'Neill]], also served as a producer.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nAlthough the film has been described as \"semi-autobiographical\",<ref name=\"RS\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/features/how-greta-gerwig-turned-the-personal-lady-bird-into-a-perfect-movie-w511093|title=How Greta Gerwig Turned the Personal 'Lady Bird' Into a Perfect Movie|website=[[Rolling Stone (magazine)|Rolling Stone]]|first=Esther|last=Zuckerman|date=November 5, 2017|accessdate=November 10, 2017}}</ref> Gerwig has said that \"nothing in the movie literally happened in my life, but it has a core of truth that resonates with what I know\".<ref name=\":0\" /> To prepare the cast and crew, Gerwig gave them her old high-school yearbooks, photos, and journals, as well as passages written by [[Joan Didion]], and took them on a tour of her hometown.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2017/11/greta-gerwig-lady-bird-design|title=How Greta Gerwig's Lady Bird Came to \"Look Like a Memory\"|website=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]|first=Julie|last=Miller|date=November 3, 2017|accessdate=November 10, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2017/11/greta-gerwig-lady-bird-joan-didion|title=How Joan Didion Shaped the World of Greta Gerwig's Lady Bird|last=Desta|first=Yohana|date=November 4, 2017|website=Vanity Fair|accessdate=November 10, 2017}}</ref> She told Sam Levy, [[Cinematographer|director of photography]] on the film, that she wanted it to feel \"like a memory,\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thefilmstage.com/features/lady-bird-cinematographer-sam-levy-on-greta-gerwig-frank-ocean-and-eric-rohmer/|title='Lady Bird' Cinematographer Sam Levy on Greta Gerwig, Frank Ocean, and \u00c9ric Rohmer|website=The Film Stage|first=Jordan|last=Raup|date=November 1, 2017|accessdate=November 10, 2017}}</ref> and said that she \"sought to offer a female counterpart to tales like ''[[The 400 Blows]]'' and ''[[Boyhood (film)|Boyhood]].''\"<ref name=\"RS\" /> The film was Gerwig's first as a solo director; in 2008, she had co-written and co-directed ''[[Nights and Weekends]]'' with [[Joe Swanberg]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Simran |last=Hans |title=Lady Bird review \u2013 a magical portrait of adolescence |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/feb/18/lady-bird-review-greta-gerwig-saoirse-ronan-laurie-metcalf-observer |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]] |date=February 18, 2018 |accessdate=February 21, 2018 |quote=\"''Lady Bird'' has been described as Greta Gerwig\u2019s directorial debut. Yet, with ... a co-director credit on Joe Swanberg's 2008 mumblecore drama ''Nights and Weekends'', it's not as though she is new to making movies.\"}}</ref>\n\n===Casting===\nIn September 2015, Gerwig met with [[Saoirse Ronan]] at the [[Toronto International Film Festival]], where they were promoting ''[[Maggie's Plan]]'' and [[Brooklyn (film)|''Brooklyn'']] respectively. They ran through the script in a hotel room, with Ronan reading the part of Lady Bird, and Gerwig reading the other characters. Gerwig realized by the second page that Ronan was the right choice for the lead.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-et-mn-greta-gerwig-lady-bird-telluride-20170903-htmlstory.html|title=Greta Gerwig talks about her directorial debut and casting Saoirse Ronan in 'Lady Bird'|website=[[Los Angeles Times]]|first=Josh|last=Rottenberg|date=September 3, 2017|accessdate=November 10, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://collider.com/greta-gerwig-interview-lady-bird/|title=Greta Gerwig on 'Lady Bird' and What Made Saoirse Ronan Perfect for the Title Role|last=Radish|first=Christina|date=November 8, 2017|website=[[Collider (website)|Collider]]|accessdate=November 10, 2017}}</ref> In January 2016, Ronan was cast.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/saoirse-ronan-greta-gerwig-lady-bird-1201686272/|title=Saoirse Ronan starring in Greta Gerwig's Drama Lady Bird|website=Variety|first=Dave|last=McNary|date=January 22, 2016|accessdate=September 28, 2017}}</ref> Gerwig met with [[Lucas Hedges]] and offered him his choice of the male parts. He chose Danny.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vulture.com/2017/11/lucas-hedges-on-lady-bird-three-billboards-and-boy-erased.html|title=Lucas Hedges Is Obsessed With His Lady Bird Co-stars, and Kept His Puka Shell Necklace|website=[[Vulture.com]]|first=Jackson|last=McHenry|date=November 8, 2017|accessdate=November 10, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wmagazine.com/story/lucas-hedges-lady-bird-greta-gerwig-madonna-oscars-party-gigi-hadid|title=Lucas Hedges Confesses He Was Almost Thrown Out of Madonna's Oscars Party|website=[[W Magazine]]|first=Lynn|last=Hirschberg|date=November 2, 2017|accessdate=November 10, 2017}}</ref> Gerwig cast [[Laurie Metcalf]] after seeing her theater work;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2017/11/lady-bird-laurie-metcalf-on-mom-role-and-roseanne-revival|title=Lady Bird's Laurie Metcalf on the Mom Role That Hit Close to Home and Roseanne's Revival|website=Vanity Fair|first=Nicole|last=Sperling|date=November 2, 2017|accessdate=November 10, 2017}}</ref> the rest of the cast\u2014including [[Tracy Letts]], [[Timoth\u00e9e Chalamet]], [[Beanie Feldstein]], [[John Karna]] and [[Jordan Rodrigues]]\u2014was announced in September 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2016/09/john-karna-lady-bird-natasha-liu-bordizzo-hotel-mumbai-1201814887/|title=John Karna Joins 'Lady Bird' Bevy; Natasha Liu Bordizzo Checks Into 'Hotel Mumbai'|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Amanda|last=N'Duka|date=September 7, 2016|accessdate=September 8, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2016/09/greta-gerwigs-lady-bird-jordan-rodrigues-pacific-rim-2-cailee-spaeny-1201820544/|title=Greta Gerwig's 'Lady Bird' Adds Jordan Rodrigues; Cailee Spaeny Cast In 'Pacific Rim: Maelstrom'|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Amanda|last=N'Duka|date=September 15, 2016|accessdate=September 15, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wmagazine.com/story/beanie-feldstein-jonah-hill-sister-lady-bird-movie-greta-gerwig|title=Lady Bird's Beanie Feldstein Has Boundless Potential (and the Enthusiasm to Match)|website=[[W Magazine]]|first=Lauren|last=McCarthy|date=November 2, 2017|accessdate=November 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\n[[Principal photography]] was scheduled to begin in March 2016, but was delayed to August due to Ronan's commitments to a performance of Arthur Miller's ''[[The Crucible]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ew.com/movies/2017/12/11/greta-gerwig-lady-bird-golden-globes-nomination/|title=Greta Gerwig wants to hug every Lady Bird crew member after Golden Globe nominations|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|first=Devan|last=Coggan|date=December 11, 2017|accessdate=December 11, 2017}}</ref> Filming began on August 30, 2016 in Sacramento, California for one week. Five weeks were spent on location in [[Los Angeles]],<ref name=\":1\" /> with additional shooting in [[New York City]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.backstage.com/resources/detail/productionlisting/lady-bird-85896/|title=Lady Bird|website=Backstage|accessdate=September 8, 2016}}</ref> Gerwig had wanted to shoot the movie on [[Super 16 film]], but due to budget constraints ultimately shot on the [[Arri Alexa]] Mini. In [[post-production]], the filmmakers emphasized digital [[Noise (electronics)|noise]] to create the effect of a copy of a photograph.<ref>{{Cite podcast|title=All the Way Home with Barry Jenkins & Greta Gerwig|url=https://a24films.com/notes/2018/02/episode-01-all-the-way-home-with-barry-jenkins-greta-gerwig|date=February 28, 2018|last=Gerwig|first=Greta|last2=Jenkins|first2=Barry|publisher=[[A24 (company)|a24]]|author-link2=Barry Jenkins}}</ref>\n\nRonan dyed her hair red for the role, and did not wear makeup to cover her [[acne]]; she has said she saw the film as \"a really good opportunity to let a teenager's face in a movie actually look like a teenager's face in real life\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2017/11/saoirse-ronan-lady-bird-in-character|title=Saoirse Ronan Reveals the Secrets Behind Her Stunning Lady Bird Transformation|website=Vanity Fair|first=Julie|last=Miller|date=November 9, 2017|accessdate=November 10, 2017}}</ref> Gerwig, using a technique she learned from the filmmaker [[Rebecca Miller]], arrived an hour before everyone else to put the actors and crew at ease by knowing exactly how the day would run. She also banned cell phones on the set, a policy borrowed from [[Noah Baumbach]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/greta-gerwig-on-lady-bird_us_59f9a6fee4b0b7f0915f6307|title=Greta Gerwig on \"Lady Bird\"|website=[[The Huffington Post]]|first=Neil|last=Minow|date=November 1, 2017|accessdate=November 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nIn July 2017, [[A24 (company)|A24]] acquired worldwide distribution rights to the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2017/07/lady-bird-greta-gerwig-saoirse-ronan-a24-1202130872/|title=A24 Lands Worldwide Rights To Greta Gerwig-Directed 'Lady Bird|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Mike|last=Fleming Jr|date=July 18, 2017|accessdate=July 18, 2017}}</ref> The film had its world premiere at the Telluride Film Festival on September 1, 2017,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2017/08/telluride-film-festival-2017-lineup-list-batle-of-the-sexes-1202158843/|title='Darkest Hour', 'Battle of the Sexes', 'Lady Bird' Among World Premieres in 2017 Lineup \u2013 Telluride Film Festival|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Pete|last=Hammond|date=August 31, 2017|accessdate=August 31, 2017}}</ref> and screened at the Toronto International Film Festival on September 8, 2017,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tiff.net/tiff/lady-bird/|title=Lady Bird|website=[[Toronto International Film Festival]]|accessdate=November 10, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612162703/https://www.tiff.net/tiff/lady-bird/|archive-date=June 12, 2018|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and at the [[New York Film Festival]] on October 8, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.filmlinc.org/nyff2017/films/lady-bird/|title=Lady Bird|website=[[New York Film Festival]]|accessdate=November 10, 2017}}</ref> [[Universal Pictures]] acquired international distribution rights to the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/festivals/focus-international-distribution-saoirse-ronan-lady-bird-1202554975/|title=Focus Takes International Rights on Saoirse Ronan's Lady Bird|website=Variety|accessdate= September 12, 2017}}</ref> It was released theatrically in the United States on November 3, 2017,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2017/09/lady-bird-greta-gerwig-release-date-november-1202175334/|title=Greta Gerwig's 'Lady Bird' Going a Week Earlier in November|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro|date=September 22, 2017|accessdate=September 22, 2017}}</ref> in the United Kingdom on February 16, 2018, and in Ireland on February 23, 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nme.com/news/film/critics-say-hyped-indie-film-lady-bird-2157499|title=What the critics have to say about hyped indie film 'Lady Bird'|last=Connick|first=Tom|date=November 8, 2017|work=NME|access-date=November 11, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\n''Lady Bird'' grossed $49 million in the United States and Canada, and $29.7 million in other territories, for a worldwide total of $78.6 million.<ref name=\"BOM\" />\n\nIn its limited opening weekend, it grossed $364,437 from four theaters, for a per-theater average of $91,109.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2017/11/greta-gerwig-lady-bird-gilbert-lbj-last-flag-flying-specialty-box-office-1202202222/|title=Greta Gerwig's 'Lady Bird' Takes Year's Best Per Theater Average Of $93K \u2013 Specialty Box Office|author=Brian Brooks|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|accessdate=November 5, 2017}}</ref> It had the second best theater average of 2017, and the highest ever for a film in limited release directed by a woman.<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2017/11/lady-bird-greta-gerwig-box-office-oscar-race-moonlight|title=How Greta Gerwig's Lady Bird Just Took a Big Leap Forward in the Oscar Race|author=Joanna Robinson|work=Vanity Fair|accessdate=November 6, 2017}}</ref> The film expanded to 37 theaters in its second weekend, and grossed a three-day total of $1.2&nbsp;million, finishing tenth at the box office.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://deadline.com/2017/11/thor-ragnarok-murder-on-the-orient-express-daddys-home-2-weekend-box-office-1202205662/|title='Daddy's Home 2' Higher Than 'The Orient Express' In A 'Ragnarok'-Ruled Weekend \u2013 Early Sunday AM Update|author=Anthony D'Alessandro|date=November 11, 2017|accessdate=November 11, 2017}}</ref> In its third weekend, the film expanded to 238 theaters, and grossed a three-day total of $2.5 million, finishing eighth at the box office.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2017/11/justice-league-coco-gal-gadot-wonder-roman-j-israel-esq-thanksgiving-box-office-1202212680/|title=Can \u2018Coco\u2019 Whip \u2018Justice League\u2019 For Top Spot Over Thanksgiving Stretch? \u2013 Box Office Preview|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=November 20, 2017|accessdate=November 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe film had its official wide release on November 24, playing in 724 theaters and making $4 million over the weekend ($5.4 million over the five-day [[Thanksgiving (United States)|Thanksgiving]] frame), finishing eleventh.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2017/11/coco-justice-league-wonder-thanksgiving-box-office-1202213755/|title=Thanksgiving B.O. At $268M, +3% Over 2016 Spurred By \u2018Coco\u2019 & Holdovers|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=November 26, 2017|accessdate=November 26, 2017}}</ref> Expanding to 1,194 theaters the following week the film grossed $4.3 million, returning to eighth place.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2017/12/coco-three-billboards-shape-of-water-wonder-post-thanksgiving-weekend-box-office-1202217467/|title=\u2018Coco\u2019 Looking At Sweet $26M+ As Specialty Sector Pops With Awards Contenders \u2013 Sunday Final|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=December 3, 2017|accessdate=December 3, 2017}}</ref> ''Lady Bird'' also became A24's highest-grossing film domestically, ahead of ''[[Moonlight (2016 film)|Moonlight]]'', which made $27.9 million.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.indiewire.com/2017/12/lady-bird-box-office-a24-moonlight-1201910789/|title=\u2018Lady Bird\u2019 Is Now A24\u2019s Highest-Grossing Film, Surpassing \u2018Moonlight\u2019|last=Nordine|first=Michael|date=December 24, 2017|work=IndieWire|access-date=December 29, 2017}}</ref> The weekend of January 27, 2018, following the announcement of the film's five Oscar nominations, it made $1.9 million (an increase over the previous week's $1.1 million).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2018/01/maze-runner-death-cure-weekend-box-office-1202269925/|title=Fox Controls Close To 40% Of Weekend B.O. Led By \u2018Maze Runner\u2019 & Oscar Holdovers; \u2018Hostiles\u2019 Gallops Past $10M|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=January 28, 2018|accessdate=January 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\n{{multiple image|caption_align=center|header_align=center\n|align = right\n|total_width = 300\n|image1 = Saoirse Ronan in 2018 (cropped).png\n|width1 = 380\n|height1 = 500\n|image2 = LaurieMetcalfFeb08 cropped.jpg\n|width2 = 431\n|height2 = 500\n|footer = [[Saoirse Ronan]] and [[Laurie Metcalf]]'s performances garnered widespread critical acclaim and earned them [[Academy Award]] nominations for [[Academy Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]] and [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Supporting Actress]], respectively.\n}}\n''Lady Bird'' received a standing ovation at its international premiere at the Toronto International Film Festival,<ref>{{cite web|title=Lady Bird Director Greta Gerwig knew right away that Saoirse Ronan was right for the job|url=http://www.thewrap.com/lady-bird-greta-gerwig-saoirse-ronan-right-for-the-job-exclusive-video/|work=TheWrap|accessdate=September 11, 2017}}</ref> and was praised for Ronan and Metcalf's performances, and Gerwig's direction.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/lady-bird-review-1035669|title='Lady Bird': Film Review {{!}} Telluride 2017|work=The Hollywood Reporter|access-date=September 8, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"VarietyTelluride\">{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/reviews/lady-bird-review-greta-gerwig-1202546609/|title=Telluride Film Review: Saoirse Ronan in \u2018Lady Bird\u2019|last=Debruge|first=Peter|date=September 4, 2017|work=Variety|access-date=September 8, 2017}}</ref> On [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film currently has an approval rating of 99% based on 384 reviews, with an average rating of 8.74/10. The website's critical consensus reads \"''Lady Bird'' delivers fresh insights about the turmoil of adolescence and reveals debuting writer-director Greta Gerwig as a fully formed filmmaking talent.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/lady_bird |title=Lady Bird (2017) |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]] |access-date=March 31, 2020}}</ref> On November 27, 2017, it became the most-reviewed film ever to remain at 100% on the site with 164 positive reviews, beating previous record holder ''[[Toy Story 2]]'', which had 163 positive reviews at the time.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://ew.com/movies/2017/11/27/lady-bird-rotten-tomatoes-record/|title='Lady Bird' sets Rotten Tomatoes record as best-reviewed movie of all time|last=Weldon|first=Sarah|date=November 27, 2017|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|accessdate=September 19, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> It [[List of films with a 100% rating on Rotten Tomatoes|stayed at 100%]] until the 196th review was negative.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2017/12/lady-bird-rotten-tomatoes-record-broken-bad-review-cole-smithey-1201906394/|title=\u2018Lady Bird\u2019 No Longer Has a Perfect 100% on Rotten Tomatoes (and Nobody is Happy About It)|last=Sharf|first=Zack|date=December 11, 2017|website=[[IndieWire]]|url-status=live|access-date=September 19, 2019}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a weighted average score of 94 out of 100, based on reviews from 50 critics, indicating \"universal acclaim.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/lady-bird|title=Lady Bird Reviews|work=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|url-status=live|accessdate=September 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[A.O. Scott]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' described ''Lady Bird'' as \"big-screen perfection&nbsp;... exceptionally well-written, full of wordplay and lively argument. Every line sounds like something a person might actually say, which means that the movie is also exceptionally well acted.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Review: Greta Gerwig\u2019s \u2018Lady Bird\u2019 Is Big-Screen Perfection|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/10/31/movies/lady-bird-review-greta-gerwig-saoirse-ronan.html|work= [[The New York Times]]|date=October 31, 2017|accessdate=November 21, 2017}}</ref> [[Todd McCarthy]] of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' wrote the film was \"modestly scaled but creatively ambitious\" and \"succeeds on its own terms as a piquant audience pleaser\", and gave praise to Ronan, whom he said \"just seems to keep getting better all the time.\"<ref>{{cite news|title='Lady Bird:' Film Review Telluride 2017|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/lady-bird-review-1035669/|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=October 30, 2017}}</ref> Peter Debruge of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' praised Gerwig's direction and script as well as Ronan's performance.<ref name=VarietyTelluride/> [[Mick LaSalle]] of the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'' wrote the film was \"simply beautiful\" and \"warm and inspired\", hailing the performances of Ronan and Metcalf as well as Gerwig's direction and screenplay.<ref>{{cite news|last=LaSalle|first=Mick|title=Gerwig's 'Lady Bird' is warm and inspired|url=http://www.sfchronicle.com/movies/article/Gerwig-s-Lady-Bird-is-warm-and-inspired-12343275.php|accessdate=December 8, 2017|newspaper=[[San Francisco Chronicle]]|date=November 8, 2017}}</ref>\n\n''[[The Washington Post]]''{{'}}s [[Ann Hornaday]] described the film as a \"triumph of style, sensibility and spirit\" while similarly praising Ronan's performance and Gerwig's direction.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/goingoutguide/movies/greta-gerwig-makes-a-triumphant-debut-as-a-director-with-coming-of-age-comedy-lady-bird/2017/11/07/8b8bf78a-bc0c-11e7-a908-a3470754bbb9_story.html|date=November 8, 2017|title=Greta Gerwig makes a triumphant debut as a solo director with \u2018Lady Bird\u2019|work=[[The Washington Post]]|publisher=Ann Hornaday|accessdate=}}</ref> [[Peter Travers]] of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' rated the film 3.5 out of four stars in which he deemed it as \"simply irresistible\" and complimented the film's plot and narrative while highlighting the performances of Ronan and Metcalf in which he stated as an \"[[Academy Awards|Oscar]] calling\" and Gerwig's direction as \"full-blown triumph\". He also declared it as one of the year's best films.<ref>{{cite web|first=Peter|last=Travers|authorlink=Peter Travers|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/reviews/peter-travers-lady-bird-is-the-coming-of-age-movie-of-2017-w510189|title='Lady Bird' Review: Greta Gerwig's Coming-of-Age Story Is Simply Irresistible|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=October 31, 2017}}</ref> [[Richard Roeper]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' called the film \"unique and original and fresh and wonderful\" and \"appealing\" while lauding the performances (particularly Metcalf and Letts) in which he remarked that \"There\u2019s no level of acting on a higher plane than what [Metcalf] and [Letts] achieve in this film. This is what greatness looks like.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://chicago.suntimes.com/entertainment/greta-gerwigs-lady-bird-so-appealing-we-cant-wait-to-see-her-next/|title=Greta Gerwig\u2019s \u2018Lady Bird\u2019 so appealing, we can\u2019t wait to see her next|author=[[Richard Roeper]]|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|date=November 9, 2017|accessdate=November 9, 2017}}</ref> [[Alonso Duralde]] of ''[[TheWrap]]'' remarked that \"Gerwig the actress skillfully pivots between the wacky and the poignant, so it's no surprise that Gerwig the auteur so delicately balances hilarity and heartbreak\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/lady-bird-review-greta-gerwig-saoirse-ronan-laurie-metcalf/|title=\u2018Lady Bird\u2019 Film Review: Greta Gerwig Crafts a Lovely Portrait of the Artist as a Young Woman|work=[[TheWrap]]|first=Alonso|last=Duralde|date=November 3, 2017|accessdate=December 8, 2017}}</ref>\n\nA [[BBC]] study described the film as the \"most overrated by critics\" among the 2018 Oscar nominees. This was based on the difference in aggregated scores given to it by critics and collated by Metacritic compared to the scores given to it by the public on the website [[IMDb]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-43146027|title= Oscars 2018: Lady Bird is 'most overrated' nominated film by critics|author= Clara Guibourg|date= March 3, 2018 |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=August 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{{Main|List of accolades received by Lady Bird (film)}}\n''Lady Bird'' garnered a variety of awards and nominations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/feature/2017-film-awards-and-nominations-scorecard?|title=Best of 2017: Film Awards and Nominations Scorecard|website=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=January 3, 2018}}</ref> The film was chosen by the [[National Board of Review]], the [[American Film Institute]], and ''Time'' magazine as one of the top 10 films of 2017.<ref name=\"AFI\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalboardofreview.org/2017/11/national-board-review-announces-2017-award-winners/|title=National Board of Review Announces 2017 Award Winners|date=November 28, 2017|publisher=[[National Board of Review]]|accessdate=December 7, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://time.com/5045566/top-10-movies-2017/|title=The Top 10 Movies of 2017|last=Zacharek|first=Stephanie|authorlink=Stephanie Zacharek|date=December 7, 2017|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|accessdate=December 13, 2017}}</ref> In 2018, ''Lady Bird'' was awarded [[The ReFrame Stamp]] in the [[The ReFrame Stamp#2017 Narrative & Animated Feature Recipients|2017 Narrative & Animated Feature]] category.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://womenandhollywood.com/reframe-spotlights-gender-balanced-films-and-tv-with-new-stamp/|title=ReFrame Spotlights Gender-Balanced Films and TV with New Stamp|last=|first=|date=June 8, 2018|website=womenandhollywood.com|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[90th Academy Awards]], it was nominated for [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]], [[Academy Award for Best Director|Best Director]] and [[Academy Award for Best Original Screenplay|Best Original Screenplay]] for Gerwig, [[Academy Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]] for Ronan, and [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Actress in a Supporting Role]] for Metcalf;<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/01/23/entertainment/greta-gerwig-lady-bird-oscar-nomination/index.html|title=Greta Gerwig's best director nomination is a huge deal|first=Sandra |last=Gonzalez|work=CNN|access-date=March 2, 2018}}</ref> Gerwig became the fifth woman nominated in the Best Director category.<ref name=\":2\" /> It did not win in any of the five categories in which it was nominated.\n\nThe film also received eight nominations at the [[23rd Critics' Choice Awards]], including [[Critics' Choice Movie Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]], [[Critics' Choice Movie Award for Best Director|Best Director]], [[Critics' Choice Movie Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]], [[Critics' Choice Movie Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Supporting Actress]], [[Critics' Choice Movie Award for Best Screenplay|Best Original Screenplay]], and [[Critics' Choice Movie Award for Best Acting Ensemble|Best Acting Ensemble]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://deadline.com/2017/12/critics-choice-awards-nominations-the-shape-of-water-dunkirk-this-is-us-netflix-1202220528/|title=Critics\u2019 Choice Awards Nominations: \u2018The Shape Of Water\u2019 Leads With 14; Netflix Tops TV Contenders|last=Hammond|first=Pete|date=December 6, 2017|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|accessdate=December 7, 2017}}</ref> At the [[75th Golden Globe Awards]], it was nominated for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Motion Picture \u2013 Musical or Comedy|Best Motion Picture \u2013 Musical or Comedy]] (won), [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Motion Picture Comedy or Musical|Best Actress \u2013 Musical or Comedy]] for Ronan (won), [[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actress \u2013 Motion Picture|Best Supporting Actress]] for Metcalf, and [[Golden Globe Award for Best Screenplay|Best Screenplay]].<ref name=\"GG\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/golden-globe-nominations-2018-nominees-full-list-1202634435/|title=Golden Globe Nominations: Complete List|last=Rubin|first=Rebecca|date=December 11, 2017|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=December 11, 2017}}</ref> At the [[24th Screen Actors Guild Awards]], it was nominated for [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Female Actor in a Leading Role|Outstanding Performance by a Female Actor in a Leading Role]] for Ronan, [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Female Actor in a Supporting Role|Outstanding Performance by a Female Actor in a Supporting Role]] for Metcalf, and [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Cast in a Motion Picture|Outstanding Performance by a Cast in a Motion Picture]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/sag-award-nominations-2018-full-list-1063931|title=SAG Award Nominations: The Complete List|date=December 13, 2017|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=December 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Potential sequels==\nIn February 2018, on an episode of ''The A24 Podcast'', Gerwig expressed interest in making [[spiritual successor]]s to ''Lady Bird'', saying \"I would like to do a quartet of Sacramento films\" modeled on the [[Neapolitan Novels]] of [[Elena Ferrante]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2018/02/greta-gerwig-elena-ferrante-lady-bird-sacramento-movies|title=Greta Gerwig Is Planning a Series of Spiritual Sequels to Lady Bird|last=Desta|first=Yohana|work=HWD|access-date=2018-03-30|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist|group=notes}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{sisterlinks|d=Q27480769|display=''Lady Bird''|c=Category:Lady Bird (film)|n=no|v=no|voy=no|m=no|mw=no|s=no|wikt=no|species=no|no}}\n* {{official}}\n* {{IMDb title}}\n* {{AllMovie title}}\n\n{{Greta Gerwig}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title = [[List of accolades received by Lady Bird (film)|Awards for ''Lady Bird'']]\n|list =\n{{Golden Globe Award Best Motion Picture Musical or Comedy}}\n{{National Society of Film Critics Award for Best Film}}\n{{New York Film Critics Circle Award for Best Film}}\n{{Vancouver Film Critics Circle Award for Best Film}}\n}}\n\n[[Category:2017 films]]\n[[Category:2010s comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:2010s coming-of-age comedy films]]\n[[Category:2010s coming-of-age drama films]]\n[[Category:2010s feminist films]]\n[[Category:2010s high school films]]\n[[Category:2010s independent films]]\n[[Category:2010s LGBT-related films]]\n[[Category:2010s teen comedy films]]\n[[Category:2010s teen drama films]]\n[[Category:A24 films]]\n[[Category:American comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:American coming-of-age films]]\n[[Category:American feminist films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American high school films]]\n[[Category:American teen comedy films]]\n[[Category:American teen drama films]]\n[[Category:American teen LGBT-related films]]<!--http://www.newnownext.com/lady-bird-gay-coming-out-scene/11/2017/-->\n[[Category:Best Musical or Comedy Picture Golden Globe winners]]\n[[Category:Films about parenting]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Greta Gerwig]]\n[[Category:Films featuring a Best Musical or Comedy Actress Golden Globe winning performance]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Scott Rudin]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Jon Brion]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2002]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2003]]\n[[Category:Films set in California]]\n[[Category:Films set in New York City]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Films shot in New York City]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Sacramento, California]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Greta Gerwig]]\n[[Category:Focus Features films]]\n[[Category:LGBT-related comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:LGBT-related coming-of-age films]]\n[[Category:2017 directorial debut films]]