{"title_page": "Demolition (2015 film)", "text_new": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = Demolition\n| image          = Demolition poster.jpg\n| border         = no\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Jean-Marc Vall\u00e9e]]\n| producer       = {{plainlist|\n* Lianne Halfon\n* Russ Smith\n* Molly Smith\n* Trent Luckinbill\n* [[Sidney Kimmel]]\n* Jean-Marc Vall\u00e9e\n* [[Thad Luckinbill]]\n* [[John Malkovich]]\n}}\n| writer         = Bryan Sipe\n| starring       = {{plainlist|\n* [[Jake Gyllenhaal]] \n* [[Naomi Watts]] \n* [[Chris Cooper]]\n* [[Judah Lewis]]\n}}\n| music          = \n| cinematography = [[Yves B\u00e9langer (cinematographer)|Yves B\u00e9langer]]\n| editing        = Jay M. Glen\n| studio         = {{plainlist|\n* [[Black Label Media]]\n* [[Sidney Kimmel Entertainment]]\n* [[Mr. Mudd]]\n* [[TSG Entertainment]]\n}}\n| distributor    = [[Fox Searchlight Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2015|9|10|[[2015 Toronto International Film Festival|TIFF]]|2016|4|8|United States}}\n| runtime        = 101 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $10 million<ref>{{cite web|url=http://powergrid.thewrap.com/project/demolition|title=Demolition (2016)|work=[[The Wrap]]|accessdate=December 2, 2016}}</ref>\n| gross          = $4.2 million<ref name=\"numbers\">{{cite web |url=http://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Demolition#tab=summary |title=Demolition (2016) |website=The Numbers |accessdate=September 17, 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Demolition''''' is a 2015 American [[drama]] film directed by [[Jean-Marc Vall\u00e9e]] and written by Bryan Sipe. The film stars [[Jake Gyllenhaal]], [[Naomi Watts]], [[Chris Cooper]], and [[Judah Lewis]]. The film opened the [[2015 Toronto International Film Festival]]<ref name=\"2015TIFF\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-33687016 |title=Toronto Film Festival 2015: Eddie Redmayne and Julianne Moore aim for double Oscar success |accessdate=July 28, 2015 |work=BBC News}}</ref> and was theatrically released on April 8, 2016, by [[Fox Searchlight Pictures]].\n\n== Plot ==\nDavis is a successful [[investment banker]] at a firm founded and run by his father-in-law Phil. His wife, Julia, is driving them when they are struck by another vehicle, killing Julia. Recovering in the hospital, he attempts to purchase some candy from a [[vending machine]] which malfunctions. Davis drafts a complaint to the vending machine manufacturer that includes some venting of his personal experiences. This leads to a series of anonymous conversations with a customer service representative, Karen Moreno, in which they end up sharing details of each other's life burdens.  Karen appears to be the only one he talks to, though tells his stories in an understated and unemotional style.  He brings this same unemotional process to work, which he has returned to much earlier than anyone expected.  Davis does tell one other person, a fellow commuter train rider that he realizes that he didn't love Julia because he doesn't feel \"...sad, or pain, or hurt...\".\n\nDavis's changing emotional state causes him to behave erratically. He notices that he is being followed by a green [[station wagon]]. The only thing Davis seems to connect with is trying to understand what's inside things, using a small toolkit to dismantle his household appliances, his work computer, a bathroom stall&mdash;eventually telling Phil that he has an urge to dismantle a 120-year-old grandmother clock in Phil's office.\n\nKaren follows Davis, talking with him on his commuter train without revealing her identity. She mistakenly leaves some identification, and Davis is sufficiently moved to track her down at home, where she lives with her boyfriend and boss, Carl, and her 15-year old troublemaker son, Chris.  When Carl goes on a long business trip, Davis bunks at her house, where they develop a deep [[Platonic love|platonic]] friendship. Chris initially dislikes Davis, but later grows not only to like him but to help Davis cope, while Davis becomes his mentor in return.\n\nDavis joins his in-laws in funding a foundation in Julia's name that will award an annual scholarship; during interviews, Davis behaves disrespectfully towards one of the award candidates, and Phil asks him to sign a transfer of his beneficiary rights in Julia's $2.6 million life insurance policy, to the scholarship fund in her name. Davis purchases demolition tools from a hardware store (and, later, a bulldozer) and, with Chris's assistance, destroys his house. When Davis finds an ultrasound of Julia's from the previous year, he is devastated that she failed to inform him.\n\nA climactic night impacts everyone. Davis brings Karen to the party for the scholarship winner, greatly troubling Julia's parents. A young man makes an inappropriate advance on Karen, and she later laughs out loud when he is introduced as the scholarship winner. Davis announces to everyone that Julia had been pregnant and kept it secret. Julia's mother tells him his wife was seeing someone else, and the child was not his and she took her to get an abortion. Returning to Karen's house, Davis finds Carl has returned and is reading the letters Davis wrote to Karen. Carl beats on Davis, which pales compared to the homophobic swarm beating that Chris receives after coming out as gay.\n\nDavis visits his wife's grave and the green [[station wagon]] arrives and a man carrying flowers gets out of the car. He is Michael, the driver of the car that killed Julia. Davis forgives Michael and he experiences flashbacks of his wife and him together and he finally cries, bringing closure. He realizes he loved his wife.\n\nDavis has turned a corner.  He reconciles with Julia's parents, asking Phil to contribute to refurbishing a [[carousel]] &ndash; destined for demolition &ndash; as a memorial for Julia.\n\nDavis receives a letter from Chris saying that he is recovering from his beating, his mother has left Carl, and Davis must be at [[Chelsea Piers#Pier 54|Pier 54]] at a particular time, which results in Davis witnessing the demolition of some waterfront buildings across the [[North River (Hudson River)|Hudson River]]. Chris watches Davis through binoculars from a nearby vantage point.\n\n== Cast ==\n* [[Jake Gyllenhaal]] as Davis Mitchell, an [[investment banker]]\n* [[Naomi Watts]] as Karen Moreno, a customer service representative and the interest of a grieving Davis\n* [[Chris Cooper]] as Phil Eastwood,<ref name=\"Cooper\" /> Davis's father in-law\n* [[Judah Lewis]] as Chris Moreno,<ref name=\"July2015Deadline\" /> Karen's son\n* [[C.J. Wilson (actor)|C.J. Wilson]] as Carl\n* [[Polly Draper]] as Margot Eastwood\n* Malachy Cleary as Davis's father\n* [[Debra Monk]] as Davis's mother\n* [[Heather Lind]] as Julia, Davis's wife\n*[[Alfredo Narciso]] as Michael (owner of green car) \n\n== Production ==\nIn May 2013, director [[Jean-Marc Vall\u00e9e]] was set to direct ''Demolition'', for a 2015 release date.<ref>{{cite news|title=Jean-Marc Vallee Set To Helm \u2018Demolition\u2019 For Mr. Mudd|url=http://www.deadline.com/2013/05/jean-marc-vallee-set-to-helm-demolition-for-mr-mudd/|accessdate=15 June 2013|newspaper=deadline.com}}</ref> On October 9, 2013, it was announced that Black Label Media would finance the film, and would co-produce along with [[Mr. Mudd]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Fleming Jr|first1=Mike|title=Black Label Media To Fund \u2018Dallas Buyers Club\u2019 Helmer\u2019s \u2018Demolition\u2019|url=http://deadline.com/2013/10/black-label-media-to-fund-dallas-buyers-club-helmers-demolition-607302/|accessdate=September 5, 2014|publisher=deadline.com|date=October 9, 2013}}</ref> On June 6, 2014, [[Jake Gyllenhaal]] was in early talks to star in the film.<ref name=Gyllenhaal>{{cite news|last1=Kroll|first1=Justin|title=Jake Gyllenhaal in Talks to Star in Jean-Marc Vallee\u2019s \u2018Demolition\u2019|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/jake-gyllenhaal-in-talks-to-star-in-jean-marc-vallees-demolition-1201215173/|accessdate=September 15, 2014|publisher=variety.com|date=June 6, 2014}}</ref> On July 21, [[Naomi Watts]] was in talks to join the film.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sneider|first1=Jeff|title=Naomi Watts in Negotiations to Join Jake Gyllenhaal in \u2018Demolition\u2019|url=http://www.thewrap.com/naomi-watts-in-negotiations-to-join-jake-gyllenhaal-in-demolition-exclusive/|accessdate=September 15, 2014|publisher=thewrap.com|date=July 21, 2014}}</ref> On September 4, Watts was confirmed cast in the film to play the female lead.<ref name=Watts>{{cite news|title=Naomi Watts Joins Jake Gyllenhaal In Jean-Marc Vallee\u2019s \u2018Demolition\u2019|url=http://deadline.com/2014/09/naomi-watts-jake-gyllenhaal-demolition-movie-jean-marc-vallee-829025/|accessdate=September 5, 2014|publisher=deadline.com|date=September 4, 2014}}</ref> On September 10, [[Chris Cooper]] was set to star in the film.<ref name=Cooper>{{cite news|last1=Fleming Jr|first1=Mike|title=Toronto: Chris Cooper Joins Jake Gyllenhaal, Naomi Watts In \u2018Demolition\u2019|url=http://deadline.com/2014/09/chris-cooper-jake-gyllenhaal-naomi-watts-demolition-832761/|accessdate=September 11, 2014|publisher=deadline.com|date=September 10, 2014}}</ref> On October 18, ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' announced that [[Fox Searchlight Pictures]] had acquired the US rights to the film, and director Vall\u00e9e said, \"I'm thrilled and excited to be back in business with Fox Searchlight. They have been wonderful, creative partners on ''[[Wild (2014 film)|Wild]]''. I look forward to collaborating again on Demolition.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=McClintock|first1=Pamela|last2=Kit|first2=Borys|title='Wild' Director Sets Next Film at Fox Searchlight|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/wild-director-sets-next-film-741348|accessdate=October 19, 2014|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=October 18, 2014}}</ref> [[Judah Lewis]]' role as the son of Watts' character Karen Moreno was confirmed on July 15, 2015.<ref name=\"July2015Deadline\" />\n\n=== Filming ===\nFilming began on September 15, 2014, in [[New York City]].<ref name=\"Watts\" /> On September 24, Gyllenhaal was spotted on the set while filming some scenes at [[John F. Kennedy International Airport]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Carpenter|first1=Cassie|title=Jake Gyllenhaal looks dreamy in a tartan blazer on the New York set of his film Demolition|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-2768948/Jake-Gyllenhaal-looks-dreamy-tartan-blazer-New-York-set-film-Demolition.html|accessdate=October 10, 2014|work=[[Daily Mail]]|date=September 25, 2014}}</ref> On October 6, Gyllenhaal and Watts were spotted on the shores of [[Coney Island]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Soldani|first1=Bianca|title=Hold on tight! Naomi Watts straddles Demolition co-star Jake Gyllenhaal for a piggyback ride as they goof around on set|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-2783024/Hold-tight-Naomi-Watts-enjoys-fun-sun-straddles-Demolition-star-Jake-Gyllenhaal-piggyback-ride-set.html|accessdate=October 10, 2014|work=[[Daily Mail]]|date=October 7, 2014}}</ref> On October 8, filming was taking place on [[Greenwich Street]] in NYC.<ref>{{cite news|title=Look out for Jake Gyllenhaal filming \u2018Demolition\u2019 in New York City this month|url=http://www.onlocationvacations.com/2014/10/08/look-out-for-jake-gyllenhaal-filming-demolition-in-new-york-city-this-month/|accessdate=October 10, 2014|publisher=onlocationvacations.com|date=October 8, 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Release ==\nOn July 15, 2015, [[Fox Searchlight Pictures]] set the film for a wide release on April 8, 2016.<ref name=July2015Deadline>{{cite news|last1=Pedersen|first1=Erik|title=Jake Gyllenhaal-Naomi Watts Drama \u2018Demolition\u2019 Gets Spring Release Date|url=http://deadline.com/2015/07/demolition-release-date-jake-gyllenhaal-naomi-watts-1201476565/|accessdate=July 16, 2015|work=deadline.com|date=July 15, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\nIn the United States and Canada, pre-release tracking suggested the film would gross $2\u20133 million from 854 theaters in its opening weekend, trailing fellow newcomers ''[[The Boss (2016 film)|The Boss]]'' ($20\u201324 million projection) and ''[[Hardcore Henry]]'' ($7\u201310 million projection).<ref name=\"preview\">{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2016/04/the-boss-hardcore-henry-demoition-batman-v-superman-box-office-preview-1201732456/ |title= Melissa McCarthy Will Try To \u2018Boss\u2019 Around \u2018BvS\u2019 At Box Office; Will \u2018Hardcore Henry\u2019 Sway Audiences? \u2014 Preview |work= deadline.com}}</ref> It ended up grossing just $1.1 million in its opening weekend, finishing 15th at the box office.<ref name=\"opening\">{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2016/04/the-weekend-box-office-batman-v-superman-melissa-mccarthy-1201734178/ |title=\u2018Batman V. Superman\u2019 Likely To Cross $300M Early Next Week; \u2018The Boss\u2019 Cashing In $21M Paycheck \u2013 B.O. Update |work= deadline.com}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\n''Demolition'' received mixed reviews from critics. On [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film has a 53% approval rating based on 202 reviews, with an average rating of 5.81/10. The site's consensus reads, \"''Demolition'' benefits from a stellar cast, even if their solid work isn't always enough to prop up a confused story that aims for profundity but too often settles for clich\u00e9s.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Demolition|publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/demolition_2016/}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a score of 49 out of 100, based on 42 critics, indicating \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Demolition|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/demolition}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.demolition-themovie.com/}}\n* {{IMDb title|1172049}}\n* {{Mojo title|demolition}}\n* {{Metacritic film|demolition}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|demolition_2016}}\n\n{{Jean-Marc Vall\u00e9e}}\n\n[[Category:2015 films]]\n[[Category:2010s comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:American comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American teen LGBT-related films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Jean-Marc Vall\u00e9e]]\n[[Category:Films set in New York City]]\n[[Category:Films shot in New York City]]\n[[Category:Mr. Mudd films]]\n[[Category:Sidney Kimmel Entertainment films]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = Demolition\n| image          = Demolition poster.jpg\n| border         = no\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Jean-Marc Vall\u00e9e]]\n| producer       = {{plainlist|\n* Lianne Halfon\n* Russ Smith\n* Molly Smith\n* Trent Luckinbill\n* [[Sidney Kimmel]]\n* Jean-Marc Vall\u00e9e\n* [[Thad Luckinbill]]\n* [[John Malkovich]]\n}}\n| writer         = Bryan Sipe\n| starring       = {{plainlist|\n* [[Jake Gyllenhaal]] \n* [[Naomi Watts]] \n* [[Chris Cooper]]\n* [[Judah Lewis]]\n}}\n| music          = \n| cinematography = [[Yves B\u00e9langer (cinematographer)|Yves B\u00e9langer]]\n| editing        = Jay M. Glen\n| studio         = {{plainlist|\n* [[Black Label Media]]\n* [[Sidney Kimmel Entertainment]]\n* [[Mr. Mudd]]\n* [[TSG Entertainment]]\n}}\n| distributor    = [[Fox Searchlight Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2015|9|10|[[2015 Toronto International Film Festival|TIFF]]|2016|4|8|United States}}\n| runtime        = 101 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $10 million<ref>{{cite web|url=http://powergrid.thewrap.com/project/demolition|title=Demolition (2016)|work=[[The Wrap]]|accessdate=December 2, 2016}}</ref>\n| gross          = $4.2 million<ref name=\"numbers\">{{cite web |url=http://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Demolition#tab=summary |title=Demolition (2016) |website=The Numbers |accessdate=September 17, 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Demolition''''' is a 2015 American [[drama]] film directed by [[Jean-Marc Vall\u00e9e]] and written by Bryan Sipe. The film stars [[Jake Gyllenhaal]], [[Naomi Watts]], [[Chris Cooper]], and [[Judah Lewis]]. The film opened the [[2015 Toronto International Film Festival]]<ref name=\"2015TIFF\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-33687016 |title=Toronto Film Festival 2015: Eddie Redmayne and Julianne Moore aim for double Oscar success |accessdate=July 28, 2015 |work=BBC News}}</ref> and was theatrically released on April 8, 2016, by [[Fox Searchlight Pictures]].\n\n== Plot ==\nDavis is a successful [[investment banker]] at a firm founded and run by his father-in-law Phil. His wife, Julia, is driving them when they are struck by another vehicle, killing Julia. Recovering in the hospital, he attempts to purchase some candy from a [[vending machine]] which malfunctions. Davis drafts a complaint to the vending machine manufacturer that includes some venting of his personal experiences. This leads to a series of anonymous conversations with a customer service representative, Karen Moreno, in which they end up sharing details of each other's life burdens.  Karen appears to be the only one he talks to, though tells his stories in an understated and unemotional style.  He brings this same unemotional process to work, which he has returned to much earlier than anyone expected.  Davis does tell one other person, a fellow commuter train rider that he realizes that he didn't love Julia because he doesn't feel \"...sad, or pain, or hurt...\".\n\nDavis's changing emotional state causes him to behave erratically. He notices that he is being followed by a green [[station wagon]]. The only thing Davis seems to connect with is trying to understand what's inside things, using a small toolkit to dismantle his household appliances, his work computer, a bathroom stall&mdash;eventually telling Phil that he has an urge to dismantle a 120-year-old grandmother clock in Phil's office.\n\nKaren follows Davis, talking with him on his commuter train without revealing her identity. She mistakenly leaves some identification, and Davis is sufficiently moved to track her down at home, where she lives with her boyfriend and boss, Carl, and her 15-year old troublemaker son, Chris.  When Carl goes on a long business trip, Davis bunks at her house, where they develop a deep [[Platonic love|platonic]] friendship. Chris initially dislikes Davis, but later grows not only to like him but to help Davis cope, while Davis becomes his mentor in return.\n\nDavis joins his in-laws in funding a foundation in Julia's name that will award an annual scholarship; during interviews, Davis behaves disrespectfully towards one of the award candidates, and Phil asks him to sign a transfer of his beneficiary rights in Julia's $2.6 million life insurance policy, to the scholarship fund in her name. Davis purchases demolition tools from a hardware store (and, later, a bulldozer) and, with Chris's assistance, destroys his house. When Davis finds an ultrasound of Julia's from the previous year, he is devastated that she failed to inform him.\n\nA climactic night impacts everyone. Davis brings Karen to the party for the scholarship winner, greatly troubling Julia's parents. A young man makes an inappropriate advance on Karen, and she later laughs out loud when he is introduced as the scholarship winner. Davis announces to everyone that Julia had been pregnant and kept it secret. Julia's mother tells him his wife was seeing someone else, and the child was not his and she took her to get an abortion. Returning to Karen's house, Davis finds Carl has returned and is reading the letters Davis wrote to Karen. Carl beats on Davis, which pales compared to the homophobic swarm beating that Chris receives after coming out as gay.\n\nDavis visits his wife's grave and the green [[station wagon]] arrives and a man carrying flowers gets out of the car. He is Michael, the driver of the car that killed Julia. Davis forgives Michael and he experiences flashbacks of his wife and him together and he finally cries, bringing closure. He realizes he loved his wife.\n\nDavis has turned a corner.  He reconciles with Julia's parents, asking Phil to contribute to refurbishing a [[carousel]] &ndash; destined for demolition &ndash; as a memorial for Julia.\n\nDavis receives a letter from Chris saying that he is recovering from his beating, his mother has left Carl, and Davis must be at [[Chelsea Piers#Pier 54|Pier 54]] at a particular time, which results in Davis witnessing the demolition of some waterfront buildings across the [[North River (Hudson River)|Hudson River]]. Chris watches Davis through binoculars from a nearby vantage point.\n\n== Cast ==\n* [[Jake Gyllenhaal]] as Davis Mitchell, an [[investment banker]]\n* [[Naomi Watts]] as Karen Moreno, a customer service representative and the interest of a grieving Davis\n* [[Chris Cooper]] as Phil Eastwood,<ref name=\"Cooper\" /> Davis\u2019s father in-law\n* [[Judah Lewis]] as Chris Moreno,<ref name=\"July2015Deadline\" /> Karen\u2019s son\n* [[C.J. Wilson (actor)|C.J. Wilson]] as Carl\n* [[Polly Draper]] as Margot Eastwood\n* Malachy Cleary as Davis's father\n* [[Debra Monk]] as Davis's mother\n* [[Heather Lind]] as Julia, Davis\u2019s wife\n*[[Alfredo Narciso]] as Michael (owner of green car) \n\n== Production ==\nIn May 2013, director [[Jean-Marc Vall\u00e9e]] was set to direct ''Demolition'', for a 2015 release date.<ref>{{cite news|title=Jean-Marc Vallee Set To Helm \u2018Demolition\u2019 For Mr. Mudd|url=http://www.deadline.com/2013/05/jean-marc-vallee-set-to-helm-demolition-for-mr-mudd/|accessdate=15 June 2013|newspaper=deadline.com}}</ref> On October 9, 2013, it was announced that Black Label Media would finance the film, and would co-produce along with [[Mr. Mudd]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Fleming Jr|first1=Mike|title=Black Label Media To Fund \u2018Dallas Buyers Club\u2019 Helmer\u2019s \u2018Demolition\u2019|url=http://deadline.com/2013/10/black-label-media-to-fund-dallas-buyers-club-helmers-demolition-607302/|accessdate=September 5, 2014|publisher=deadline.com|date=October 9, 2013}}</ref> On June 6, 2014, [[Jake Gyllenhaal]] was in early talks to star in the film.<ref name=Gyllenhaal>{{cite news|last1=Kroll|first1=Justin|title=Jake Gyllenhaal in Talks to Star in Jean-Marc Vallee\u2019s \u2018Demolition\u2019|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/jake-gyllenhaal-in-talks-to-star-in-jean-marc-vallees-demolition-1201215173/|accessdate=September 15, 2014|publisher=variety.com|date=June 6, 2014}}</ref> On July 21, [[Naomi Watts]] was in talks to join the film.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sneider|first1=Jeff|title=Naomi Watts in Negotiations to Join Jake Gyllenhaal in \u2018Demolition\u2019|url=http://www.thewrap.com/naomi-watts-in-negotiations-to-join-jake-gyllenhaal-in-demolition-exclusive/|accessdate=September 15, 2014|publisher=thewrap.com|date=July 21, 2014}}</ref> On September 4, Watts was confirmed cast in the film to play the female lead.<ref name=Watts>{{cite news|title=Naomi Watts Joins Jake Gyllenhaal In Jean-Marc Vallee\u2019s \u2018Demolition\u2019|url=http://deadline.com/2014/09/naomi-watts-jake-gyllenhaal-demolition-movie-jean-marc-vallee-829025/|accessdate=September 5, 2014|publisher=deadline.com|date=September 4, 2014}}</ref> On September 10, [[Chris Cooper]] was set to star in the film.<ref name=Cooper>{{cite news|last1=Fleming Jr|first1=Mike|title=Toronto: Chris Cooper Joins Jake Gyllenhaal, Naomi Watts In \u2018Demolition\u2019|url=http://deadline.com/2014/09/chris-cooper-jake-gyllenhaal-naomi-watts-demolition-832761/|accessdate=September 11, 2014|publisher=deadline.com|date=September 10, 2014}}</ref> On October 18, ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' announced that [[Fox Searchlight Pictures]] had acquired the US rights to the film, and director Vall\u00e9e said, \"I'm thrilled and excited to be back in business with Fox Searchlight. They have been wonderful, creative partners on ''[[Wild (2014 film)|Wild]]''. I look forward to collaborating again on Demolition.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=McClintock|first1=Pamela|last2=Kit|first2=Borys|title='Wild' Director Sets Next Film at Fox Searchlight|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/wild-director-sets-next-film-741348|accessdate=October 19, 2014|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=October 18, 2014}}</ref> [[Judah Lewis]]' role as the son of Watts' character Karen Moreno was confirmed on July 15, 2015.<ref name=\"July2015Deadline\" />\n\n=== Filming ===\nFilming began on September 15, 2014, in [[New York City]].<ref name=\"Watts\" /> On September 24, Gyllenhaal was spotted on the set while filming some scenes at [[John F. Kennedy International Airport]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Carpenter|first1=Cassie|title=Jake Gyllenhaal looks dreamy in a tartan blazer on the New York set of his film Demolition|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-2768948/Jake-Gyllenhaal-looks-dreamy-tartan-blazer-New-York-set-film-Demolition.html|accessdate=October 10, 2014|work=[[Daily Mail]]|date=September 25, 2014}}</ref> On October 6, Gyllenhaal and Watts were spotted on the shores of [[Coney Island]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Soldani|first1=Bianca|title=Hold on tight! Naomi Watts straddles Demolition co-star Jake Gyllenhaal for a piggyback ride as they goof around on set|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-2783024/Hold-tight-Naomi-Watts-enjoys-fun-sun-straddles-Demolition-star-Jake-Gyllenhaal-piggyback-ride-set.html|accessdate=October 10, 2014|work=[[Daily Mail]]|date=October 7, 2014}}</ref> On October 8, filming was taking place on [[Greenwich Street]] in NYC.<ref>{{cite news|title=Look out for Jake Gyllenhaal filming \u2018Demolition\u2019 in New York City this month|url=http://www.onlocationvacations.com/2014/10/08/look-out-for-jake-gyllenhaal-filming-demolition-in-new-york-city-this-month/|accessdate=October 10, 2014|publisher=onlocationvacations.com|date=October 8, 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Release ==\nOn July 15, 2015, [[Fox Searchlight Pictures]] set the film for a wide release on April 8, 2016.<ref name=July2015Deadline>{{cite news|last1=Pedersen|first1=Erik|title=Jake Gyllenhaal-Naomi Watts Drama \u2018Demolition\u2019 Gets Spring Release Date|url=http://deadline.com/2015/07/demolition-release-date-jake-gyllenhaal-naomi-watts-1201476565/|accessdate=July 16, 2015|work=deadline.com|date=July 15, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\nIn the United States and Canada, pre-release tracking suggested the film would gross $2\u20133 million from 854 theaters in its opening weekend, trailing fellow newcomers ''[[The Boss (2016 film)|The Boss]]'' ($20\u201324 million projection) and ''[[Hardcore Henry]]'' ($7\u201310 million projection).<ref name=\"preview\">{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2016/04/the-boss-hardcore-henry-demoition-batman-v-superman-box-office-preview-1201732456/ |title= Melissa McCarthy Will Try To \u2018Boss\u2019 Around \u2018BvS\u2019 At Box Office; Will \u2018Hardcore Henry\u2019 Sway Audiences? \u2014 Preview |work= deadline.com}}</ref> It ended up grossing just $1.1 million in its opening weekend, finishing 15th at the box office.<ref name=\"opening\">{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2016/04/the-weekend-box-office-batman-v-superman-melissa-mccarthy-1201734178/ |title=\u2018Batman V. Superman\u2019 Likely To Cross $300M Early Next Week; \u2018The Boss\u2019 Cashing In $21M Paycheck \u2013 B.O. Update |work= deadline.com}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\n''Demolition'' received mixed reviews from critics. On [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film has a 53% approval rating based on 202 reviews, with an average rating of 5.81/10. The site's consensus reads, \"''Demolition'' benefits from a stellar cast, even if their solid work isn't always enough to prop up a confused story that aims for profundity but too often settles for clich\u00e9s.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Demolition|publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/demolition_2016/}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a score of 49 out of 100, based on 42 critics, indicating \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Demolition|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/demolition}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.demolition-themovie.com/}}\n* {{IMDb title|1172049}}\n* {{Mojo title|demolition}}\n* {{Metacritic film|demolition}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|demolition_2016}}\n\n{{Jean-Marc Vall\u00e9e}}\n\n[[Category:2015 films]]\n[[Category:2010s comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:American comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American teen LGBT-related films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Jean-Marc Vall\u00e9e]]\n[[Category:Films set in New York City]]\n[[Category:Films shot in New York City]]\n[[Category:Mr. Mudd films]]\n[[Category:Sidney Kimmel Entertainment films]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCast:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (3)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Demolition_(2015_film)"}
